00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:16.980
And King Mihr-Shah says to Mani,
in the paradise of which you speak,

00:41:16.980 --> 00:41:18.900
is there a garden such as mine?

00:41:18.900 --> 00:41:23.150
Again, the Persian king is boasting
as a gardener in the 3rd Century.

00:41:23.150 --> 00:41:27.050
And then Mani showed him the
Paradise of Light, a garden.

00:41:27.050 --> 00:41:31.080
With all kinds of things, and
other desirable sights there.

00:41:31.080 --> 00:41:36.460
Almost like the Herodotus
description of actually a paradise

00:41:36.460 --> 00:41:37.760
in the [inaudible] period.

00:41:37.760 --> 00:41:45.400
And within this garden, in fact
it is imagined in textual sources

00:41:45.400 --> 00:41:49.480
as a paradise, in a
paradisiacal state.

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:54.280
And this should also remind us of
the investa and the story of Yima

00:41:54.280 --> 00:41:57.580
in [inaudible] to where he creates
this beautiful sort of enclosure

00:41:57.580 --> 00:42:01.530
where all the animals, all the
living beings, all that is good.

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:03.300
Is enclosed there.

00:42:03.300 --> 00:42:07.380
And the Sasanians created this
idea of Erih, Iranianness,

00:42:07.380 --> 00:42:10.680
and they gave values to it and
discussed it in the literature.

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:14.340
And they said within this
Iranshahr there is order --

00:42:14.340 --> 00:42:17.110
the order of the king
-- and there is beauty.

00:42:17.110 --> 00:42:20.770
And of course it's the King's
Justice that keeps this idea going.

00:42:20.770 --> 00:42:24.430
And that is a theme that we find
in Middle Eastern Literature.

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:28.960
The idea of sort of a just
state and the Circle of Justice.

00:42:28.960 --> 00:42:31.650
Which has a much more ancient
tradition but certainly

00:42:31.650 --> 00:42:36.270
in the early Islamic period it
borrows from the Sasanian times.

00:42:36.270 --> 00:42:39.690
Now, if there is this
beauty, justice, and order,

00:42:39.690 --> 00:42:43.030
