02:11:31.130 --> 02:11:36.250
And in addition, I'd like to
thank all of you for coming out.

02:11:36.250 --> 02:11:39.460
Okay, let me see if I
know how to use this.

02:11:39.460 --> 02:11:45.960
Okay, shortly after his
restoration to the throne in 591,

02:11:45.960 --> 02:11:49.540
the Sasanian King Khosrow
II presented two remarkable

02:11:49.540 --> 02:11:53.080
benefactions to the shrine of
the Christian Saint Surgius

02:11:53.080 --> 02:11:55.700
in Byzantine Sergiopolis.

02:11:55.700 --> 02:12:01.450
For the first, Khosrow restored
to the shrine a cross taken

02:12:01.450 --> 02:12:05.070 position:56%
in an earlier period of estrangement
between Byzantium and Iran

02:12:05.070 --> 02:12:08.550
and provided a second cross
inscribed with the king's thanks

02:12:08.550 --> 02:12:11.550
to the saint for aiding
in his removal

02:12:11.550 --> 02:12:14.770
of the usurper Bahram Chobin.

02:12:14.770 --> 02:12:18.930
The second gift contained
a number of things --

02:12:18.930 --> 02:12:24.290
a number of varied gifts and a
plate inscribed, "Not for the sight

02:12:24.290 --> 02:12:27.350
of men," giving the
king's thanks to the saint

02:12:27.350 --> 02:12:31.830
for helping his Christian
wife Shirin conceive a child.

02:12:31.830 --> 02:12:33.830
Kho row's devotion to the shrine

02:12:33.830 --> 02:12:38.090
of St. Sergius displays the complex
interconnections of faith, power,

02:12:38.090 --> 02:12:40.900
and legitimacy in the
late ancient world.

02:12:40.900 --> 02:12:44.610
Khosrow came to power in a coup
against his father, Hormizd IV,

02:12:44.610 --> 02:12:48.200
orchestrated by his uncles
from the aristocratic house

02:12:48.200 --> 02:12:50.340
of the Ispahbudhan.

02:12:50.340 --> 02:12:54.700
Khosrow was then in turn deposed
by the Chief General of his empire,

02:12:54.700 --> 02:12:59.280
Bahram Chobin, scion of another
of the empire's great families.

02:12:59.280 --> 02:13:02.930
Forced to flee to the protection
of the Byzantine Emperor Maurice,

02:13:02.930 --> 02:13:05.410
Khosrow's restoration to
the throne was supported

02:13:05.410 --> 02:13:08.600
by a foreign Christian ruler,
and more significantly,

02:13:08.600 --> 02:13:11.010
by his own Christian subjects.

02:13:11.010 --> 02:13:14.980
Khosrow's thank offerings to a
Christian military saint popular

02:13:14.980 --> 02:13:19.620 position:56%
in both Byzantine and Sasanian lands
emphasized the harmonious relations

02:13:19.620 --> 02:13:23.140
between Khosrow and the
Christians of the Sasanian East,

02:13:23.140 --> 02:13:27.810
and the prominent role of
his wife in shaping them.

02:13:27.810 --> 02:13:30.590
Shirin, paramount Queen of Khosrow,

02:13:30.590 --> 02:13:34.100 position:56%
is one of the best documented
figures of the late Sasanian period,

02:13:34.100 --> 02:13:38.370 position:56%
appearing in numerous accounts of
Greek -- in Greek, Armenian, Syriac,

02:13:38.370 --> 02:13:41.200
Arabic, Persian, and
other languages.

02:13:41.200 --> 02:13:44.960
Her central role in the poetry
of later Persian authors

02:13:44.960 --> 02:13:48.280
such as Ferdowsi and
Nizami testifies

02:13:48.280 --> 02:13:50.820
to her continuing importance
in the mythologizing

02:13:50.820 --> 02:13:53.890
of the pre-Islamic
kings of Iranshahr.

02:13:53.890 --> 02:13:56.600
Yet as a Christian,
she appears especially

02:13:56.600 --> 02:13:58.430 position:56%
in early historical accounts written

02:13:58.430 --> 02:14:01.170
within the empire's diverse
Christian communities,

02:14:01.170 --> 02:14:04.230
the East Syrian Church
of the East, West Syrian

02:14:04.230 --> 02:14:07.880
and Armenian miaphysite
Christian churches,

02:14:07.880 --> 02:14:10.420
Caucasian Albanian,
and Chalcedonian.

02:14:10.420 --> 02:14:13.810
Well, it can be difficult
to sort the myth

02:14:13.810 --> 02:14:17.290
from the late Sasanian
reality of Shirin.

02:14:17.290 --> 02:14:20.590
Here status as queen, courtier,
and Christian provides us

02:14:20.590 --> 02:14:22.920
with a fascinating window
into the complex place

02:14:22.920 --> 02:14:25.510
of Christians in the Sasanian East.

02:14:25.510 --> 02:14:29.600
As a subordinate minority
population, as vital supporters

02:14:29.600 --> 02:14:34.640
of Sasanian dynastic power, and as
a rapidly-expanding religious --

02:14:34.640 --> 02:14:37.970
set of religious communities
locked in complex intra-

02:14:37.970 --> 02:14:41.030
and inter-confessional competition.

02:14:41.030 --> 02:14:45.230
The Sasanian world was home to
significant Christian populations

02:14:45.230 --> 02:14:48.070
at least as far back
as the third century.

02:14:48.070 --> 02:14:49.710
From the start, the
Christian communities

02:14:49.710 --> 02:14:53.570 position:56%
of the Sasanian Empire were diverse,
originating in distinct episodes

02:14:53.570 --> 02:14:58.650
of proselytization and sometimes
deportation, of culturally,

02:14:58.650 --> 02:15:02.470
geographically, and linguistically
disparate populations.

02:15:02.470 --> 02:15:05.520 position:56%
One of the more significant cultural
divides among Christians was the

02:15:05.520 --> 02:15:07.980
organization of churches
around urban communities

02:15:07.980 --> 02:15:10.340
in greater Mesopotamia
and Khuzestan,

02:15:10.340 --> 02:15:14.140
and around aristocratic families
and inherited priestly offices

02:15:14.140 --> 02:15:17.440
in the Armenian high lands, and
perhaps the Iranian Plateau.

02:15:17.440 --> 02:15:20.790
We've already heard about
that from Steve's talk.

02:15:20.790 --> 02:15:24.140 position:56%
Thus, one might make an argument for
the existence of distinct lowland

02:15:24.140 --> 02:15:26.420
and highland churches
in Sasanian lands,

02:15:26.420 --> 02:15:30.280
the former serving largely
Aramean and Greek audiences,

02:15:30.280 --> 02:15:33.860
the latter encompassing
Iranians, Armenians, Iberians,

02:15:33.860 --> 02:15:35.270
and Caucasian Albanians,

02:15:35.270 --> 02:15:41.870
often lumped together
conceptually as Arians.

02:15:41.870 --> 02:15:45.080
The growth of the Sasanian Empire's
Christian communities did not go

02:15:45.080 --> 02:15:46.750
unnoticed by the Sasanian kings

02:15:46.750 --> 02:15:49.480
and the Zoroastrian
elites of their empire.

02:15:49.480 --> 02:15:52.830
The third and fourth century saw
several episodes of persecutions

02:15:52.830 --> 02:15:58.440
by Zoroastrian priests and
supporters of the Sasanian dynasty.

02:15:58.440 --> 02:16:01.600
However, these generally arose in
periods of conflict between Iran

02:16:01.600 --> 02:16:04.730
and Christian Byzantium when
Sasanian Christians were seen

02:16:04.730 --> 02:16:08.290
as a sort of fifth column
for the empire to the west.

02:16:08.290 --> 02:16:11.580
However, as Zoroastrians tended
to view their faith as a marker

02:16:11.580 --> 02:16:16.070
of ethnicity, a characteristic
specifically of Arian peoples,

02:16:16.070 --> 02:16:18.820
the fiercest opposition to
Christianity arose from instances

02:16:18.820 --> 02:16:23.170
of Arian apostasy, particularly
in the kingdoms of Caucasia

02:16:23.170 --> 02:16:26.390
and among the aristocrats
of the Iranian Plateau.

02:16:26.390 --> 02:16:28.070
Nevertheless, efforts
to stem the spread

02:16:28.070 --> 02:16:31.180
of Christianity among Sasanian
subjects were piecemeal

02:16:31.180 --> 02:16:34.140
and ultimately futile,
for reasons which are kind

02:16:34.140 --> 02:16:36.410
of outside the scope of this paper.

02:16:36.410 --> 02:16:41.120
By the time of Shirin in the sixth
and seventh century, our sources,

02:16:41.120 --> 02:16:44.020
admittedly mostly Christian
and anecdotal,

02:16:44.020 --> 02:16:47.390
suggest that Christians made up an
absolute majority of the population

02:16:47.390 --> 02:16:50.830
of the empire's western
regions, Greater Caucasia,

02:16:50.830 --> 02:16:55.790
Greater Mesopotamia, and Shirin's
probable homeland, Khuzestan.

02:16:55.790 --> 02:16:57.490
By the early seventh century,

02:16:57.490 --> 02:17:01.340
the East Syrian Synotacon Orientali
[assumed spelling] documents an

02:17:01.340 --> 02:17:04.230
extensive network of
episcopacies stretching

02:17:04.230 --> 02:17:08.610
across the Sasanian
realm into Central Asia.

02:17:08.610 --> 02:17:11.710
Christian churches,
martyria, monasteries,

02:17:11.710 --> 02:17:16.820
and other holy sites came to
dot the Sasanian countryside.

02:17:16.820 --> 02:17:19.870
While few Sasanian Christian
sites have seen systematic modern

02:17:19.870 --> 02:17:23.780 position:56%
excavation, circuitous collection
of artifacts supports the impression

02:17:23.780 --> 02:17:28.890
of an intensive Christianization
of the late Sasanian landscape.

02:17:28.890 --> 02:17:33.810
It is perhaps not surprising, then,
that the Sasanian kings sought

02:17:33.810 --> 02:17:37.890
to assert their authority over the
Christian's spiritual landscape

02:17:37.890 --> 02:17:39.530
of their empire.

02:17:39.530 --> 02:17:41.510
Earlier kings had been
somewhat uncomfortable

02:17:41.510 --> 02:17:44.240
with the direct support
of Christian shrines.

02:17:44.240 --> 02:17:47.960
Indeed, in the fifth century
Yazdegerd I even allowed the

02:17:47.960 --> 02:17:52.040
Byzantine bishop Marutha of
Maipherqat to remove all the relics

02:17:52.040 --> 02:17:55.610
of Christians martyred in Sasanian
lands to his [inaudible] back home

02:17:55.610 --> 02:17:57.270
in the Byzantine Empire,

02:17:57.270 --> 02:18:00.070
which Marutha then
renamed Martyropolis,

02:18:00.070 --> 02:18:02.990
the city of the martyrs.

02:18:02.990 --> 02:18:05.750 position:56%
Yet with his Christian Queen Shirin,

02:18:05.750 --> 02:18:08.970
Khosrow became an enthusiastic
patron of Christian holy sites,

02:18:08.970 --> 02:18:11.030
churches, and monasteries.

02:18:11.030 --> 02:18:14.500
The Syriac "Life of the
Catholicos [inaudible]" notes

02:18:14.500 --> 02:18:18.940
that Shirin induced her husband
to build a monastery in Ctesiphon,

02:18:18.940 --> 02:18:22.930
while other sources describe the
construction and provisioning

02:18:22.930 --> 02:18:25.120
of the church and monastery
associated

02:18:25.120 --> 02:18:28.670
with the massive Sasanian
royal complex of Qasr-e Shirin.

02:18:28.670 --> 02:18:32.340
Oops, this one there.

02:18:32.340 --> 02:18:35.170
This presents a number
of interesting questions.

02:18:35.170 --> 02:18:39.560 position:56%
Was Shirin truly the inspiration for
royal patronage of Christian sites?

02:18:39.560 --> 02:18:43.120
Was Shirin a convenient front for
the king to support Christians

02:18:43.120 --> 02:18:45.740
without alienating
Zoroastrian nobles and priests?

02:18:45.740 --> 02:18:49.060
Do our Christian writers
intentionally overstate the

02:18:49.060 --> 02:18:52.910
influence of Shirin and
Christian power during the reign

02:18:52.910 --> 02:18:54.820
of Khosrow II?

02:18:54.820 --> 02:18:57.940
Whatever the specific
answers here, royal patronage

02:18:57.940 --> 02:19:01.650
of Christian holy sites served to
raise the profile of these places,

02:19:01.650 --> 02:19:03.740
strengthen the bonds
between Christian subjects

02:19:03.740 --> 02:19:07.320
and Sasanian king, and
assert royal authority

02:19:07.320 --> 02:19:10.690
over the Christian holy sites.

02:19:10.690 --> 02:19:12.570
Christian writers were, however,

02:19:12.570 --> 02:19:16.840
eager to emphasize the
limits of royal power.

02:19:16.840 --> 02:19:19.940
Take, for example, the account
in the Armenian [speaking

02:19:19.940 --> 02:19:23.250
in foreign language] in which
he describes Shirin's efforts

02:19:23.250 --> 02:19:29.230
to thwart Khosrow's transfer of
the bones of the prophet Daniel,

02:19:29.230 --> 02:19:32.070
portrayed in this image
as an Iranian aristocrat

02:19:32.070 --> 02:19:37.460
and also probably a eunuch,
from Shush to Khuzestan --

02:19:37.460 --> 02:19:41.880
Shush in Khuzestan into the
hands of the Byzantine emperor.

02:19:41.880 --> 02:19:44.820
The queen asked the people
of Shush to pray to Christ

02:19:44.820 --> 02:19:47.800
to thwart her husband's
efforts, and was rewarded

02:19:47.800 --> 02:19:49.670
with miraculous intervention

02:19:49.670 --> 02:19:51.710
when the prophet's bones
left the city gate,

02:19:51.710 --> 02:19:53.780
all of the city's springs dried up

02:19:53.780 --> 02:19:57.670
and the mules pulling the litter
refused to abandon the city.

02:19:57.670 --> 02:20:01.350
When Daniel returned to his
home, its springs gushed forth

02:20:01.350 --> 02:20:05.520
and the King of Kings and the
Byzantine emperor alike were forced

02:20:05.520 --> 02:20:08.280
to bow to the will of God.

02:20:08.280 --> 02:20:11.080
Curiously, though, in making
its point about the limits

02:20:11.080 --> 02:20:14.630
of royal power, the story
presents Shirin as a champion

02:20:14.630 --> 02:20:18.650
of a uniquely Sasanian
Christianity, opposed to foreigners

02:20:18.650 --> 02:20:21.930
who might steal divine
grace from Iranshahr,

02:20:21.930 --> 02:20:26.110
like Marutha who I've already
mentioned in the fifth century.

02:20:26.110 --> 02:20:28.750
Indeed, Sasanian kings and
their Christian subjects came

02:20:28.750 --> 02:20:32.700
to collaborate openly and directly
from the fifth century onward.

02:20:32.700 --> 02:20:35.480
Christians, being outside the
empire's traditional political

02:20:35.480 --> 02:20:38.930
elites, were potentially more
reliable supporters of the dynasty

02:20:38.930 --> 02:20:42.530
than the fiercely independent
great families of Iran.

02:20:42.530 --> 02:20:46.240
After convening a Christian
senate at Ctesiphon in 410,

02:20:46.240 --> 02:20:49.390
the kings allowed Christians to
worship openly, and the Church

02:20:49.390 --> 02:20:54.820
of the East -- the Syrian Church of
the East was officially recognized

02:20:54.820 --> 02:20:57.870
as temporal authority
of the King of Kings.

02:20:57.870 --> 02:21:01.480
In return for tolerance,
Christian clerics, especially those

02:21:01.480 --> 02:21:05.750 position:56%
of this East Syrian Church, offered
their prayers for the king and acted

02:21:05.750 --> 02:21:09.980
as mediators between the King of
Kings and the Christian subjects.

02:21:09.980 --> 02:21:12.380
After this settlement, it
was increasingly common

02:21:12.380 --> 02:21:16.210
to see Christians in service to the
Sasanian dynasty, with the clergy

02:21:16.210 --> 02:21:18.360
of the Church of the
East even acting overtly,

02:21:18.360 --> 02:21:22.450
and sometimes covertly,
as agents as the king.

02:21:22.450 --> 02:21:25.670
While the Sasanian kings
remained resolutely Zoroastrian,

02:21:25.670 --> 02:21:29.670
Sasanian Christians increasingly
saw Iranshahr and its kings

02:21:29.670 --> 02:21:33.880
as instruments of God's will,
and also saw the submission

02:21:33.880 --> 02:21:37.680
of Zoroastrian elites and the king
to the Christian God and savior

02:21:37.680 --> 02:21:41.070
as only a matter of
time, inevitable.

02:21:41.070 --> 02:21:43.580
Khosrow's marriage to a
Christian and Shirin's prominence

02:21:43.580 --> 02:21:47.930
at court fed this popular
perception of Christian triumph.

02:21:47.930 --> 02:21:50.590
We may see this in the
seventh century Armenian vision

02:21:50.590 --> 02:21:54.210
of the nativity where the
magi are clearly portrayed

02:21:54.210 --> 02:21:56.820
as Sasanian aristocrats
offering their submission

02:21:56.820 --> 02:22:00.410
to Christ and the virgin.

02:22:00.410 --> 02:22:04.650
Shirin, the queen of queens, served
as the pole star for constellations

02:22:04.650 --> 02:22:07.590
of Christian notables
at Khosrow II's court.

02:22:07.590 --> 02:22:11.100 position:56%
Christian physicians like the
queen's favorite, Gabriel of Sinjar,

02:22:11.100 --> 02:22:13.100 position:56%
attended to the king and his family.

02:22:13.100 --> 02:22:14.500
And many of the top financial

02:22:14.500 --> 02:22:17.140
and military officials
serving the dynasty,

02:22:17.140 --> 02:22:19.040
like the finance minister Yazdin

02:22:19.040 --> 02:22:21.660
and the Armenian General Sinbad
Digortuni [assumed spelling],

02:22:21.660 --> 02:22:23.060
were Christians.

02:22:23.060 --> 02:22:26.580 position:56%
These Christian grandees advanced at
court with the enthusiastic support

02:22:26.580 --> 02:22:31.160
of the queen and rewarded the
king with their loyal service.

02:22:31.160 --> 02:22:34.150
Christian clergy and holy men
also found places at court

02:22:34.150 --> 02:22:36.350
under Shirin's sponsorship.

02:22:36.350 --> 02:22:39.710
For some, the queen
provided protection.

02:22:39.710 --> 02:22:41.620
The Armenian Catholicos
Viroi [assumed spelling],

02:22:41.620 --> 02:22:45.030
implicated in a revolt,
fled to the queen at court

02:22:45.030 --> 02:22:49.150
and was spared execution
as a present from the king.

02:22:49.150 --> 02:22:53.020
Viroi remained an honored prisoner
at court for the next 25 years,

02:22:53.020 --> 02:22:56.570
learning Persian, which we I think
would all agree is probably a much

02:22:56.570 --> 02:22:58.490
better fate than the
death, mutilation,

02:22:58.490 --> 02:23:02.260
or banishment suffered
by his other rebels.

02:23:02.260 --> 02:23:05.440
Shirin's favor at court could
establish a clergyman's power

02:23:05.440 --> 02:23:08.430 position:56%
and status in both church and state.

02:23:08.430 --> 02:23:12.170 position:56%
East Syrian sources describe how
Shirin introduced the Ascetic Bishop

02:23:12.170 --> 02:23:16.730
Sabrisho of Lashom to the
king, providing miraculous aid

02:23:16.730 --> 02:23:19.470
to the king during his civil
wars and acting as go-between

02:23:19.470 --> 02:23:20.770
with the Byzantine emperor.

02:23:20.770 --> 02:23:24.680 position:56%
Sabrisho became Shirin and Khosrow's
clear choice for Catholicos

02:23:24.680 --> 02:23:26.390
of the Church of the East.

02:23:26.390 --> 02:23:29.690
After securing his
election, Sabrisho served

02:23:29.690 --> 02:23:33.430
as the queen's confessor and an
important advisor to the king.

02:23:33.430 --> 02:23:35.790
Indeed, Sabrisho died on campaign,

02:23:35.790 --> 02:23:39.830
with Khosrow having helped
suppress a revolt in Nisibis.

02:23:39.830 --> 02:23:43.460 position:56%
Notably, though, the East
Syrian-Khuzestan Chronicle condemned

02:23:43.460 --> 02:23:47.840
Shirin for her role in elevating
Sabrisho's successor, her favorite,

02:23:47.840 --> 02:23:49.660
Gregory of Phrat, in place

02:23:49.660 --> 02:23:52.000
of her husband's preferred
candidate Gregory

02:23:52.000 --> 02:23:54.420
of Kashgar, the Bishop of Nisibis.

02:23:54.420 --> 02:23:57.680
According to the story, she
tricked the assembled bishops

02:23:57.680 --> 02:24:00.970
because they both were named
Gregory, so she implied

02:24:00.970 --> 02:24:03.160
that her husband preferred
one Gregory

02:24:03.160 --> 02:24:05.320
over the other, and it was not.

02:24:05.320 --> 02:24:09.420 position:56%
Apparently, Khosrow furiously
thereafter ordered the newly-elected

02:24:09.420 --> 02:24:13.270
catholicos to ransom a bunch of
Christian books and pay him a sort

02:24:13.270 --> 02:24:17.850
of one-time payment to
get out of the doghouse.

02:24:17.850 --> 02:24:19.330 position:56%
Well, this story is a bit ludicrous.

02:24:19.330 --> 02:24:22.480
It's a little hard to imagine that
either bishops or king would be

02:24:22.480 --> 02:24:26.590
so easily swayed by the simple
fact of a coincidence of names.

02:24:26.590 --> 02:24:31.340
Khosrow did refuse
to allow the election

02:24:31.340 --> 02:24:37.030
of a new catholicos
after Gregory's death.

02:24:37.030 --> 02:24:39.630
And this brings us to a
sort of final point --

02:24:39.630 --> 02:24:41.170
or final section of the paper.

02:24:41.170 --> 02:24:44.640
While our sources attest to
Shirin's power in the empire

02:24:44.640 --> 02:24:47.270
and its churches, her actions
are often denigrated in some

02:24:47.270 --> 02:24:51.850
of our sources, most notably Syrian
ones like the Khuzestan Chronicle.

02:24:51.850 --> 02:24:54.560
While some of this was rooted
in contemporary opposition

02:24:54.560 --> 02:24:58.380
to female authority over matters
political and theological,

02:24:58.380 --> 02:24:59.980
it also reflects the intra-

02:24:59.980 --> 02:25:04.140 position:56%
and inter-communal debates among the
Christians of the Sasanian realm.

02:25:04.140 --> 02:25:08.740
From the 410 senate of Ctesiphon
to the time of Khosrow II,

02:25:08.740 --> 02:25:13.530
the East Syrian Church of the
East had served as something akin

02:25:13.530 --> 02:25:15.910
to an official state church.

02:25:15.910 --> 02:25:18.550
As we've seen, East Syrian
clergy proved willing

02:25:18.550 --> 02:25:21.150
to accommodate themselves
to royal power.

02:25:21.150 --> 02:25:23.720
However, their prominence
was increasingly challenged

02:25:23.720 --> 02:25:28.260
by a new Christian movement
within the empire who Shirin came

02:25:28.260 --> 02:25:31.030
to become the champion of.

02:25:31.030 --> 02:25:33.660
Matters of theology
became increasingly central

02:25:33.660 --> 02:25:36.900
in defining Christian communities
by the sixth and seventh century.

02:25:36.900 --> 02:25:41.780 position:56%
In a politically-wise move, Sasanian
Christians largely rejected the

02:25:41.780 --> 02:25:47.850
two-nature Christology adopted
at the 451 counsel of Chalcedon

02:25:47.850 --> 02:25:52.170
as a Greek innovation imposed
by the Byzantine emperors.

02:25:52.170 --> 02:25:53.470
The most significant churches

02:25:53.470 --> 02:25:57.400
of late Sasanian Iranshahr adopted
either a distinct anti-king,

02:25:57.400 --> 02:26:00.770
two-natures Christology -- I
won't get into the details of this

02:26:00.770 --> 02:26:02.880
because it's horrifically
complicated --

02:26:02.880 --> 02:26:08.360 position:56%
or an Alexandrian single-nature
Christology, which would be the sort

02:26:08.360 --> 02:26:12.100
of miaphysite West Syrian
and Armenian churches.

02:26:12.100 --> 02:26:16.190
In the sixth century, the sort of
up-and-coming miaphysite preachers,

02:26:16.190 --> 02:26:19.740
some of them who had been driven
out of the Byzantine Empire,

02:26:19.740 --> 02:26:22.900
made significant inroads
in Sasanian territories.

02:26:22.900 --> 02:26:24.200
Sasanian Christians --

02:26:24.200 --> 02:26:29.450
sorry, Armenian Christians taking
an anti-Chalcedonian stance

02:26:29.450 --> 02:26:33.430
at the Councils of [inaudible],
endorsed a miaphysite creed,

02:26:33.430 --> 02:26:36.810
while the enormously-influential
Assyrian fathers of Iberia,

02:26:36.810 --> 02:26:40.950 position:56%
now seen as paragons of Chalcedonian
orthodoxy in modern Georgia,

02:26:40.950 --> 02:26:44.100
probably spread miaphysite
teachings, too.

02:26:44.100 --> 02:26:46.470
The Syriac theological
school in the politically-

02:26:46.470 --> 02:26:51.000
and strategically-vital city
of Nisibis became a flash point

02:26:51.000 --> 02:26:55.480
for debate and conflict between
duaphysite and miaphysite teachers.

02:26:55.480 --> 02:26:57.320
Indeed, the breakup of that
school around the beginning

02:26:57.320 --> 02:27:00.450
of the seventh century must be seen
against this doctrinal conflict,

02:27:00.450 --> 02:27:03.290
as well as court politics.

02:27:03.290 --> 02:27:07.430
Indeed, miaphysites seem to
have had growing influence

02:27:07.430 --> 02:27:10.590
in the Sasanian court going
into the early seventh century.

02:27:10.590 --> 02:27:13.990
The Armenian church won
particular favor with Khosrow

02:27:13.990 --> 02:27:17.120
as Armenian generals and troops
supported him in his restoration

02:27:17.120 --> 02:27:20.450
to the throne, and his wars
with his rebellious uncles,

02:27:20.450 --> 02:27:24.790
and conflicts with the Turks on
the empire's eastern frontier.

02:27:24.790 --> 02:27:29.030
Culturally, the miaphysite Armenian
church's aristocratic orientation

02:27:29.030 --> 02:27:32.120 position:56%
was also a somewhat more comfortable
fit with the social dynamics

02:27:32.120 --> 02:27:35.500
of the Sasanian aristocracy.

02:27:35.500 --> 02:27:39.110
However, for many East Syrian
authors, the triumph of heresy

02:27:39.110 --> 02:27:42.110
at court was due entirely to Shirin

02:27:42.110 --> 02:27:45.920
and to her silver-tongued
serpent Gabriel of Sinjar.

02:27:45.920 --> 02:27:48.240
The physician Gabriel was a
particular favorite of Shirin's

02:27:48.240 --> 02:27:51.650
for helping the queen bear a
son, and was intensely involved

02:27:51.650 --> 02:27:53.920
in the politics of the
Church of the East.

02:27:53.920 --> 02:27:56.640
However, following his
excommunication from that church

02:27:56.640 --> 02:27:59.380
for bigamy, Gabriel
became a vocal advocate

02:27:59.380 --> 02:28:02.170
for the miaphysite
position at church.

02:28:02.170 --> 02:28:05.470
Gabriel's failed attempts to
promote a miaphysite to catholicos

02:28:05.470 --> 02:28:07.530
at the East Syrian
Church contributed

02:28:07.530 --> 02:28:12.350
to the office remaining
vacant for almost two decades.

02:28:12.350 --> 02:28:15.390
Gabriel and the miaphysite theology
he endorsed enjoyed the queen's

02:28:15.390 --> 02:28:18.320
increasingly enthusiastic support.

02:28:18.320 --> 02:28:21.620
However, miaphysitism
really got its biggest boost

02:28:21.620 --> 02:28:27.800 position:56%
from the Sasanian conquest of much
of the Byzantine East where a number

02:28:27.800 --> 02:28:32.220
of disgruntled miaphysites lived,
and where Khosrow was happy

02:28:32.220 --> 02:28:37.680
to accommodate them by
appointing miaphysite bishops.

02:28:37.680 --> 02:28:41.500
This all comes together ultimately
at an instant that's described

02:28:41.500 --> 02:28:46.650
in a number of sources, sometimes
called the Senate of the Persians,

02:28:46.650 --> 02:28:49.500
which appears to have
been held sometime

02:28:49.500 --> 02:28:54.030
in the second decade
of the seventh century.

02:28:54.030 --> 02:28:57.490
At this senate there seems to
have been some sort of attempt

02:28:57.490 --> 02:29:01.540
to establish a state version
of Christianity centered

02:29:01.540 --> 02:29:03.740
around miaphysitism,
or at least to try

02:29:03.740 --> 02:29:06.120
and reconcile the various
doctrinal differences

02:29:06.120 --> 02:29:08.350
between the Christian factions.

02:29:08.350 --> 02:29:12.280
The Armenian [inaudible] describes
this senate as the Persians

02:29:12.280 --> 02:29:17.080
in some detail as a dispute between
the orthodox, for him miaphysites,

02:29:17.080 --> 02:29:19.070
which included the
queen, Gabriel of Sinjar,

02:29:19.070 --> 02:29:22.640
and other various West
Syrian and Armenian bishops.

02:29:22.640 --> 02:29:27.090
The East Syrian, Iran Catholicos
and his supporters on another side,

02:29:27.090 --> 02:29:31.830 position:56%
and various Greek supporters of the
Chalcedonian creed, along with Viroi

02:29:31.830 --> 02:29:34.290
who was hanging out at court.

02:29:34.290 --> 02:29:36.880
In [inaudible] telling,
Khosrow ordered the --

02:29:36.880 --> 02:29:42.210
also ordered the Jewish Chief
Rabbi, who showed up uninvited,

02:29:42.210 --> 02:29:45.620
unceremoniously expelled and
beaten from the conference

02:29:45.620 --> 02:29:48.780
for denying the divinity of Christ.

02:29:48.780 --> 02:29:52.610
But nevertheless, what seems
to be happening here is --

02:29:52.610 --> 02:29:55.090
you know, at least
across our sources,

02:29:55.090 --> 02:29:58.520
is that Khosrow was not entirely
prepared to sever his kind

02:29:58.520 --> 02:30:01.910
of traditional alliance with the
Church of the East, but was hoping

02:30:01.910 --> 02:30:04.530
to sort of harmonize the
Church of the East with a sort

02:30:04.530 --> 02:30:08.880
of growing miaphysite community who
were of vital strategic importance

02:30:08.880 --> 02:30:12.050
in the frontier regions
of the empire.

02:30:12.050 --> 02:30:16.180
Khosrow's capture of Jerusalem
and the true cross in 614,

02:30:16.180 --> 02:30:18.530
and the seeming inevitability
of his final victory

02:30:18.530 --> 02:30:21.250
over the Chalcedonian
emperors in Constantinople,

02:30:21.250 --> 02:30:23.060
made Khosrow a leading
candidate for --

02:30:23.060 --> 02:30:26.280
as legitimate earthly
king of all Christians.

02:30:26.280 --> 02:30:30.190
In this role, the king sought a
place above the fray, supporting

02:30:30.190 --> 02:30:33.450 position:56%
and controlling Christian
institutions even-handedly while his

02:30:33.450 --> 02:30:35.910
wife and Christian court
officials concerned themselves

02:30:35.910 --> 02:30:38.140
with the messy business
of engaging with

02:30:38.140 --> 02:30:41.000 position:56%
and managing the Christian minority.

02:30:41.000 --> 02:30:44.740 position:56%
In the end, though, Khosrow's
dreams of universal dominion failed.

02:30:44.740 --> 02:30:48.380
Although his Christian subjects had
proved among his most loyal allies,

02:30:48.380 --> 02:30:51.050
even in a conflict with
a Christian emperor,

02:30:51.050 --> 02:30:55.780
his highest courtiers abandoned
him when the tide of war turned.

02:30:55.780 --> 02:30:59.190
Making common-cause with
his disinherited son,

02:30:59.190 --> 02:31:01.530
the nobles in the empire
deposed and killed the king.

02:31:01.530 --> 02:31:07.690
And then the -- Khosrow's son then
executed all the other male members

02:31:07.690 --> 02:31:10.020
of the dynasty, including
the sons of Shirin.

02:31:10.020 --> 02:31:14.010
As for Shirin, we have
two counts of her fate.

02:31:14.010 --> 02:31:20.530 position:56%
One has -- a Syrian source in Arabic
has her avenge the death of her son

02:31:20.530 --> 02:31:22.800
by poisoning Kavadh, the new king.

02:31:22.800 --> 02:31:27.970
In the "Shahnameh," she commits
suicide upon Khosrow's grave rather

02:31:27.970 --> 02:31:31.100
than being forced to marry his son.

02:31:31.100 --> 02:31:33.990 position:56%
But despite her fate, Shirin gives a
fascinating glimpse into the heights

02:31:33.990 --> 02:31:37.240
to which a Christian woman might
ascend in the Sasanian Empire,

02:31:37.240 --> 02:31:39.570
the manner in which
Christians and their --

02:31:39.570 --> 02:31:42.050
or Sasanians and their
Christian subjects were united

02:31:42.050 --> 02:31:45.450
and bound together by ties
of patronage and patriotism,

02:31:45.450 --> 02:31:46.900
and the centrality of Christians

02:31:46.900 --> 02:31:50.080
in the late Sasanian world
in all their diversity.

02:31:50.080 --> 02:31:52.850
The enduring Churches of
the East would serve as one

02:31:52.850 --> 02:31:55.870
of the great legacies
of Sasanian Iranshahr.

02:31:55.870 --> 02:31:57.670
Thank you.

02:31:57.670 --> 02:32:03.710
[ Applause ]

02:32:03.710 --> 02:32:05.830
&gt;&gt; Fatemeh Keshavarz: Thank you
very much, Professor McDonough,

02:32:05.830 --> 02:32:11.240
for that fascinating account
of exchanges and interactions.

02:32:11.240 --> 02:32:14.940
Of course, being a scholar
of Persian literature,

02:32:14.940 --> 02:32:17.820
all the way through I was
thinking of the Shirin

02:32:17.820 --> 02:32:22.270
that [inaudible] introduced to
us, conveniently, of course,

02:32:22.270 --> 02:32:27.930
converted to Islam, even
though her Armenian origins are

02:32:27.930 --> 02:32:32.010
repeatedly explained.

02:32:32.010 --> 02:32:38.100
But the most fascinating part for
me is that as he ends that story,

02:32:38.100 --> 02:32:42.510
he tells us that this is
about nobody but Shirin.

02:32:42.510 --> 02:32:55.260
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

02:32:55.260 --> 02:32:59.710
And then he takes that even one
step further and connects Shirin

02:32:59.710 --> 02:33:02.510
with his own wife, Ahfah
[assumed spelling].

02:33:02.510 --> 02:33:09.540
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

02:33:09.540 --> 02:33:11.400
So Shirin is alive and well.

02:33:11.400 --> 02:33:15.200
And for those who don't speak
Persian, [inaudible] basically says

02:33:15.200 --> 02:33:21.490 position:56%
that this whole story is about
Shirin, and that lived a short life,

02:33:21.490 --> 02:33:24.840
and my wife reminded me
of that, and so I built

02:33:24.840 --> 02:33:27.640
that story on Shirin for you.

02:33:27.640 --> 02:33:33.310
So with that we look forward to the
last presentation of this panel,

02:33:33.310 --> 02:33:36.430
which will bring hopefully
for us more

02:33:36.430 --> 02:33:44.160
of a Jewish interaction
into the picture.

02:33:44.160 --> 02:33:48.140
And the presenter is
Professor Simcha Gross

02:33:48.140 --> 02:33:52.400
who is an Assistant Professor
of History of Late Antiquity

02:33:52.400 --> 02:33:57.740
or Antique Judaism at the
University of California, Irvine.

02:33:57.740 --> 02:34:00.820
So we have so far had
two illustrious speakers

02:34:00.820 --> 02:34:02.940
from that university.

02:34:02.940 --> 02:34:05.680
Dr. Gross got his PhD

02:34:05.680 --> 02:34:10.380
at Yale University Department
of Religious Studies.

02:34:10.380 --> 02:34:13.370
And his work is very much focused

02:34:13.370 --> 02:34:19.190
on creating and/or providing
an integrative account

02:34:19.190 --> 02:34:23.630
of the three elements of
Jews, serial Christians,

02:34:23.630 --> 02:34:28.480
and the larger Sasanian
Islamic Empire.

02:34:28.480 --> 02:34:33.740
So it's a very integrative reading
of that, which we will look forward

02:34:33.740 --> 02:34:39.570
to the presentation of
Dr. Gross's talk today.

02:34:39.570 --> 02:34:45.750
The title of it is "Kings or
Slaves, Babylonian Jewish Claims

02:34:45.750 --> 02:34:50.580
of Royal Genealogy in
Their Sasanian Context."

02:34:50.580 --> 02:34:53.510
Please welcome Professor Gross.

02:34:53.510 --> 02:35:01.730
[ Applause ]

02:35:01.730 --> 02:35:03.910
&gt;&gt; Simcha Gross: I'm in the
uncomfortable position of standing

02:35:03.910 --> 02:35:07.180
between Fatemeh's Persian
Poetry and lunch,

02:35:07.180 --> 02:35:12.560
so I'll try to get to the point.

02:35:12.560 --> 02:35:16.430
I want to thank the
organizers, sponsors,

02:35:16.430 --> 02:35:19.520
and all of you for attending.

02:35:19.520 --> 02:35:24.960
Am I up? As long as there
were Persian empires,

02:35:24.960 --> 02:35:26.420
there were Jews living in them.

02:35:26.420 --> 02:35:29.350
From the Achaemenids, through
the Sasanians, through the Shah,

02:35:29.350 --> 02:35:32.390
to the present day, Jews
have always been a fixture

02:35:32.390 --> 02:35:34.430
of Persian imperial rule.

02:35:34.430 --> 02:35:37.370
Yet of all the Persian empires,
arguably the most important

02:35:37.370 --> 02:35:39.800
for Jewish history was
the Sasanian Empire.

02:35:39.800 --> 02:35:41.470
The Jews who lived under
the Sasanian Empire,

02:35:41.470 --> 02:35:46.030
primarily in Sasanian Iraq --
so that's on the right-hand side

02:35:46.030 --> 02:35:48.240
of the map -- produced
the Babylonian Talmud,

02:35:48.240 --> 02:35:49.540
the crowning literary achievement

02:35:49.540 --> 02:35:52.470
of Jewish Antiquity whose
production essentially coincided

02:35:52.470 --> 02:35:55.180
with nearly the entire
Sasanian period.

02:35:55.180 --> 02:35:58.030
The texts, rituals, and stories
that this community produced became

02:35:58.030 --> 02:35:59.780
and continue to be
normative for most Jews

02:35:59.780 --> 02:36:01.080
around the world to this day.

02:36:01.080 --> 02:36:04.760
And yet only recently have
scholars turned their attention

02:36:04.760 --> 02:36:07.140
to the Sasanian context
of these Jews.

02:36:07.140 --> 02:36:09.890
These scholars have mostly shown
that Babylonian Jews were consumers

02:36:09.890 --> 02:36:13.410
of the rich range of
literatures, mythologies, stories,

02:36:13.410 --> 02:36:15.160
and even legal discussions
of the various groups

02:36:15.160 --> 02:36:17.860
that inhabited the Sasanian
Empire, including Zoroastrians,

02:36:17.860 --> 02:36:20.020
Syriac Christians,
Manichaeans, Mandaeans, and more.

02:36:20.020 --> 02:36:21.860
The richest example

02:36:21.860 --> 02:36:23.680
of this cross-cultural
exchange may be the hundreds

02:36:23.680 --> 02:36:25.300
of incantation bowls produced

02:36:25.300 --> 02:36:27.870
by these various groups
in Late Antiquity.

02:36:27.870 --> 02:36:31.910 position:56%
As you can see from the image above,
we have bowls inscribed in Mandaic,

02:36:31.910 --> 02:36:35.600
Syriac, and Jewish Babylonian
Aramaic, and even Middle Persian.

02:36:35.600 --> 02:36:38.160
These incantation bowls were
not only similar in form,

02:36:38.160 --> 02:36:41.720
they were oftentimes nearly
identical in their formula as well.

02:36:41.720 --> 02:36:43.020
These bowls show how the borders

02:36:43.020 --> 02:36:44.930
between these various
groups were far more porous

02:36:44.930 --> 02:36:47.430
than their texts would
often have us believe.

02:36:47.430 --> 02:36:50.850
Thus, a bowl written in Jewish
Babylonian Aramaic invokes

02:36:50.850 --> 02:36:54.110
Zoroastrian, Babylonian,
Christian, and Jewish mythology,

02:36:54.110 --> 02:36:57.470
as well as what appears to
be early Yazidi mythology.

02:36:57.470 --> 02:37:00.120
Together, the scholarly
textual studies as well

02:37:00.120 --> 02:37:01.420
as the increased publication

02:37:01.420 --> 02:37:03.760
of these incantation
bowls make it quite clear

02:37:03.760 --> 02:37:07.170
that Babylonian Jews had access to
other groups and their traditions.

02:37:07.170 --> 02:37:08.980
These studies have enriched
our understanding of the ways

02:37:08.980 --> 02:37:11.700
in which the various groups that
inhabited the same empire were

02:37:11.700 --> 02:37:13.310
at times in conversation
with one another.

02:37:13.310 --> 02:37:16.020 position:56%
They have also shown that these
groups can only be fully appreciated

02:37:16.020 --> 02:37:18.380
within their larger context.

02:37:18.380 --> 02:37:22.010
Today I want to move beyond these
moments of contact between groups

02:37:22.010 --> 02:37:23.640
and ask a broader question.

02:37:23.640 --> 02:37:28.020
In what ways were Babylonian
Jews Persianized or Sasanianized?

02:37:28.020 --> 02:37:29.750
In what ways did Babylonian
Jews interact

02:37:29.750 --> 02:37:31.680
with the Sasanian Empire
and its administration?

02:37:31.680 --> 02:37:35.280
In what ways did they accept,
reject, subvert, manipulate,

02:37:35.280 --> 02:37:37.710
and otherwise negotiate the
norms and practices supported

02:37:37.710 --> 02:37:39.680
by their imperial context?

02:37:39.680 --> 02:37:42.120
A number of studies have
revealed the tip of the iceberg.

02:37:42.120 --> 02:37:44.490
For instance, Judith
Lerner, who's here today --

02:37:44.490 --> 02:37:46.820
sorry for calling you out --

02:37:46.820 --> 02:37:49.350
has shown how Jews and
Christians both used

02:37:49.350 --> 02:37:51.640
and subverted the imagery
on Sasanian seals.

02:37:51.640 --> 02:37:54.060
We've actually seen a number
of coins today that do this.

02:37:54.060 --> 02:38:00.650 position:56%
And so in this example on the left
you have the Zoroastrian fire priest

02:38:00.650 --> 02:38:02.580
-- or priest, rather,
with the fire alter.

02:38:02.580 --> 02:38:04.530
And on the right you seem to
have the binding of Isaac,

02:38:04.530 --> 02:38:06.830
even with the ram stuck
in the brush on the side.

02:38:06.830 --> 02:38:10.260
Other scholars have shown how
Sasanian imperial propaganda

02:38:10.260 --> 02:38:13.140
in the forms of inscriptions and
stories were known to and used

02:38:13.140 --> 02:38:15.680
by Jews and Syriac Christians in
their own literary productions.

02:38:15.680 --> 02:38:18.350
I want to offer a broader profile

02:38:18.350 --> 02:38:21.190
of what a single Jewish
household aspiring to a position

02:38:21.190 --> 02:38:24.020
as a Persian elite may have looked
like in the Sasanian Empire.

02:38:24.020 --> 02:38:25.710
We have the most evidence

02:38:25.710 --> 02:38:27.820
for one very important
Babylonian Jewish household

02:38:27.820 --> 02:38:29.890
that adopted elite Persian norms.

02:38:29.890 --> 02:38:32.810
The head of this family was known
as the Exilarch, the rosh galut

02:38:32.810 --> 02:38:35.320
in Hebrew, or reysh
galuta in Aramaic.

02:38:35.320 --> 02:38:37.060
And this title was
hereditary, passed on to one

02:38:37.060 --> 02:38:39.370
of his children upon
the Exilarch's death.

02:38:39.370 --> 02:38:41.460
The members of this family,
the children, sons-in-law,

02:38:41.460 --> 02:38:44.630
and their [inaudible] were all part
of the household of the Exilarch.

02:38:44.630 --> 02:38:47.270
Thankfully, the Exilarchy has
recently received a comprehensive

02:38:47.270 --> 02:38:51.130
study by Geoffrey Herman, to
which I am deeply indebted.

02:38:51.130 --> 02:38:53.720
Given that nearly all of our
surviving sources about Jews living

02:38:53.720 --> 02:38:56.260
in the Sasanian Empire during this
period are from texts composed

02:38:56.260 --> 02:38:59.000
by rabbis now embedded
in the Babylonian Talmud,

02:38:59.000 --> 02:39:02.570
we only get a glimpse of the
Exilarch through the rabbis' eyes.

02:39:02.570 --> 02:39:05.060
The rabbis did not always have a
particularly flattering perspective

02:39:05.060 --> 02:39:07.530
of the Exilarch, but their
criticisms are quite revealing,

02:39:07.530 --> 02:39:09.790
precisely because they were
bothered by the Persianization

02:39:09.790 --> 02:39:12.000
of the Exilarch and his household.

02:39:12.000 --> 02:39:14.140
Moreover, alongside the Exilarch,

02:39:14.140 --> 02:39:16.300
they critique the other
similar elite Jewish households,

02:39:16.300 --> 02:39:18.620
revealing that the Exilarch was
not the only Jewish household

02:39:18.620 --> 02:39:20.720
to adopt elite Persian norms.

02:39:20.720 --> 02:39:23.520
To be sure, the bias of the
rabbis against the Exilarch

02:39:23.520 --> 02:39:26.280
and other Jewish families means we
have to be cautious when reading

02:39:26.280 --> 02:39:28.260
and evaluating their remarks.

02:39:28.260 --> 02:39:30.510
However, there is also a benefit
to the polemical character

02:39:30.510 --> 02:39:32.420
of their remarks, as
the [inaudible] position

02:39:32.420 --> 02:39:34.760
to the Exilarch reflects
the rabbi's own relationship

02:39:34.760 --> 02:39:37.210
to the Persian elite norms.

02:39:37.210 --> 02:39:39.290
The contrast between these
groups will give us insight

02:39:39.290 --> 02:39:41.840
into the different attitudes Jews
may have had toward Sasanian elite

02:39:41.840 --> 02:39:43.870
norms and provide us with
a more granular perspective

02:39:43.870 --> 02:39:47.550
of different Jewish
strata in Sasanian society.

02:39:47.550 --> 02:39:49.990
The rabbis have a sustained
critique of a member

02:39:49.990 --> 02:39:52.980
of the Exilarch's household, Rav
Nahman, in a single location.

02:39:52.980 --> 02:39:55.710
This critique is not unique,
but rather representative

02:39:55.710 --> 02:39:57.820
of larger themes concerning
the Exilarch found throughout

02:39:57.820 --> 02:39:59.120
rabbinic literature.

02:39:59.120 --> 02:40:03.340
In this story, a rabbi named Rav
Yehuda appears before the member

02:40:03.340 --> 02:40:07.100
of the household of the Exilarch
named, again, Rav Nahman.

02:40:07.100 --> 02:40:08.400
In their initial discussion,

02:40:08.400 --> 02:40:11.390
Rev Yehuda continuously critiques
Rav Nahman's grandiloquence.

02:40:11.390 --> 02:40:13.080
I'm going to be reading
from this now.

02:40:13.080 --> 02:40:16.940
"Said Rav Nahman of the Exilarch's
household to Rave Yehuda,

02:40:16.940 --> 02:40:20.890
"Sit down on a karpita,""
which is some sort of a seat.

02:40:20.890 --> 02:40:24.250
"Rave Yehuda asked, "Is not safsal
as used by the Rabbis, or iztaba,

02:40:24.250 --> 02:40:28.130 position:56%
as commonly used, good enough?""
Meaning why are you using that word?

02:40:28.130 --> 02:40:32.190
There are so many other words
that we rabbis or common Jews use.

02:40:32.190 --> 02:40:35.370
"Rav Nahman continued, "Will
you partake of etronga,""

02:40:35.370 --> 02:40:37.690
which seems to be a citron.

02:40:37.690 --> 02:40:40.130
"Rav Yehuda replied,
"Thus did Samuel say,

02:40:40.130 --> 02:40:43.640
"He who says etronga is a
third puffed up with arrogance.

02:40:43.640 --> 02:40:45.510
Either Etrog, as it is
called by the rabbis,

02:40:45.510 --> 02:40:48.830
or etroga as it is
popularly called."

02:40:48.830 --> 02:40:51.920
"Will you drink anbaga,"
he asked him.

02:40:51.920 --> 02:40:54.680
"Are you then dissatisfied
with isparagus, as it is called

02:40:54.680 --> 02:40:57.930
by the rabbis, or anpak, as
it is popularly pronounced,"

02:40:57.930 --> 02:40:59.230
he reproved him."

02:40:59.230 --> 02:41:01.980
In each of these cases, Rav
Yehuda critiques Rav Nahman

02:41:01.980 --> 02:41:05.680
for using an arrogant or
haughty vocabulary word.

02:41:05.680 --> 02:41:08.720
If we pay attention, two of these
three words are Middle Persian,

02:41:08.720 --> 02:41:13.080
etronga and anbaga, and one
is Greek or Latin, karpita.

02:41:13.080 --> 02:41:14.710
According to this passage,
the member of --

02:41:14.710 --> 02:41:17.080
the members of the Exilarch's
household use different vocabulary

02:41:17.080 --> 02:41:18.570
than did the rabbis or common folk,

02:41:18.570 --> 02:41:21.520
and these words tended
to be Middle Persian.

02:41:21.520 --> 02:41:23.350
I only brought three examples
here, but there are a few others

02:41:23.350 --> 02:41:25.690
in the story used by Rav Nahman
that are also Middle Persian,

02:41:25.690 --> 02:41:27.880
and we'll see a few
of them as we go on.

02:41:27.880 --> 02:41:30.460
So for the moment it seems that
Rav Yehuda critiques Rav Nahman

02:41:30.460 --> 02:41:33.520
for using a highfalutin vocabulary
dominated by Middle Persian Words.

02:41:33.520 --> 02:41:38.210
The story continues by mocking
Rav Nahman's more liberal attitude

02:41:38.210 --> 02:41:40.020
toward women.

02:41:40.020 --> 02:41:44.250
""Let my daughter Donag come and
serve drink," Rav Nahman proposed.

02:41:44.250 --> 02:41:46.450
"Thus said Samuel,"
Rav Yehuda replied,

02:41:46.450 --> 02:41:47.860
"One must not make use of a woman."

02:41:47.860 --> 02:41:51.090
"But she is only a child,"
answered Rav Nahman.

02:41:51.090 --> 02:41:55.960
"Samuel distinctly said, "One must
make no use at all of a woman,

02:41:55.960 --> 02:41:57.840
whether adult or child,""
responded Rav Yehuda.

02:41:57.840 --> 02:42:01.960
"Will you send a greeting to my
wife Yalta," Rav Nahman suggested.

02:42:01.960 --> 02:42:03.700
"Thus said Samuel,"
Rav Yehuda replied,

02:42:03.700 --> 02:42:05.440
"to listen to a woman's
voice is indecent."

02:42:05.440 --> 02:42:08.700
"Is it possible through a
messenger," asked Rav Nahman.

02:42:08.700 --> 02:42:11.250
"Thus said Samuel, " Rave Yehuda
retorted, "One must not inquire

02:42:11.250 --> 02:42:12.870
after a woman's welfare."

02:42:12.870 --> 02:42:14.500
"Then by her husband,"
said Rav Nahman.

02:42:14.500 --> 02:42:17.680
"Thus said Samuel," said Rav
Yehuda, "One must not inquire

02:42:17.680 --> 02:42:20.120
after a woman's welfare at
all."" As you'll notice,

02:42:20.120 --> 02:42:23.280
Samuel can basically be made to
say whatever Rav Yehuda wants.

02:42:23.280 --> 02:42:26.160
In round two of their exchange,
Rav Yehuda now critiques Rav Nahman

02:42:26.160 --> 02:42:27.460
for what he continues --

02:42:27.460 --> 02:42:30.490
what he considers to be Rav
Nahman's liberal approach to women.

02:42:30.490 --> 02:42:31.890 position:56%
Rav Yehuda essentially expects women

02:42:31.890 --> 02:42:35.100
to remain entirely out
of the sight of men.

02:42:35.100 --> 02:42:37.150
Rav Nahman's approach, however,
is once again in keeping

02:42:37.150 --> 02:42:41.200 position:56%
with what we can tell about Persian
attitudes toward women at this time.

02:42:41.200 --> 02:42:44.380 position:56%
In laws found in the approximately
seventh century [inaudible] of "Book

02:42:44.380 --> 02:42:47.760
of a Thousand Judgments," "Madayan
I Hazar I Dadestan," for example,

02:42:47.760 --> 02:42:50.630
women have the right to reject
marriages arranged by their father

02:42:50.630 --> 02:42:53.860
and are given other rights of
property and responsibility.

02:42:53.860 --> 02:42:56.270
The Sasanian attitude toward women
may also be gleaned from the fact

02:42:56.270 --> 02:42:58.140
that the goddess Anahid
was a central figure

02:42:58.140 --> 02:43:00.310
in the Sasanian pantheon.

02:43:00.310 --> 02:43:04.240 position:56%
Moreover, as noted by Yaakov Elman,
Rav Nahman's daughter's name, Donag,

02:43:04.240 --> 02:43:07.360
is in fact better pronounced
as Danog, the name of the wife

02:43:07.360 --> 02:43:10.480
and queen of the first king
of the Sasanian Empire.

02:43:10.480 --> 02:43:13.920
In fact, this name is itself
Persian and probably means follower

02:43:13.920 --> 02:43:16.020
of the Den, the Zoroastrian
way of life,

02:43:16.020 --> 02:43:19.010
a striking name for a Jewish woman.

02:43:19.010 --> 02:43:21.380 position:56%
The Exilarch's household was thus
known for its more liberal treatment

02:43:21.380 --> 02:43:23.540
of women, treatment that
conforms more closely

02:43:23.540 --> 02:43:25.140
to Persian than rabbinic norms.

02:43:25.140 --> 02:43:29.340 position:56%
The Exilarch and his household also
adopted other trappings of nobility.

02:43:29.340 --> 02:43:30.670
To give one example, the Exilarch

02:43:30.670 --> 02:43:31.970
and his household were
often depicted

02:43:31.970 --> 02:43:35.170
as traveling while
borne on golden thrones.

02:43:35.170 --> 02:43:37.240
Elsewhere in the Babylonian
Talmud, the Rav Nahman

02:43:37.240 --> 02:43:39.900
of our story appears again,
this time on a golden throne.

02:43:39.900 --> 02:43:41.200
That's the story on the slide.

02:43:41.200 --> 02:43:46.300
In the Middle Persian source "Arda
Wiraz-namag," Arda Wiraz travels

02:43:46.300 --> 02:43:48.880
to the afterlife, in which
he sees, among other things,

02:43:48.880 --> 02:43:51.300
nobles seated on golden thrones.

02:43:51.300 --> 02:43:53.830
In fact, the Babylonian Talmud once
again uses a Middle Persian word

02:43:53.830 --> 02:43:55.430
to describe the throne,
the same word used

02:43:55.430 --> 02:43:56.730 position:56%
in "Arda Wiraz-namag," which is gah.

02:43:56.730 --> 02:44:00.020
This is just one example
of the elite regalia

02:44:00.020 --> 02:44:02.850
that the Exilarch seems
to have adopted.

02:44:02.850 --> 02:44:05.300
I would like to suggest
one more major way

02:44:05.300 --> 02:44:08.630 position:56%
in which the Exilarch adopted
certain aspects of Persian nobility.

02:44:08.630 --> 02:44:13.210
The most famous detail about the
Exilarch's household is its claim

02:44:13.210 --> 02:44:15.180
of genealogical descent
from King David.

02:44:15.180 --> 02:44:18.480 position:56%
For instance, there's a rabbinic
discussion in which it is determined

02:44:18.480 --> 02:44:19.850
that when the Torah
scroll is brought

02:44:19.850 --> 02:44:22.930
into public everyone
should follow behind it,

02:44:22.930 --> 02:44:24.870
thereby embodying the
figurative idea

02:44:24.870 --> 02:44:27.280
of following the Torah's
instructions.

02:44:27.280 --> 02:44:29.090
In response to this, a rabbi notes

02:44:29.090 --> 02:44:32.650
that in Babylonia the Torah is
actually brought to the Exilarch.

02:44:32.650 --> 02:44:33.950
He doesn't follow behind it.

02:44:33.950 --> 02:44:35.250
It is brought to him.

02:44:35.250 --> 02:44:37.080
And I'm quoting, "Everywhere
you say that one goes

02:44:37.080 --> 02:44:38.790
after the Torah scroll, but behold,

02:44:38.790 --> 02:44:41.290
there in Babylonia they bring
the Torah before the Exilarch!

02:44:41.290 --> 02:44:44.680
Rav Yose be-Rav Bun said, "In
that instance, since the seed

02:44:44.680 --> 02:44:47.800 position:56%
of David is embedded there, they act
for him accordance with the custom

02:44:47.800 --> 02:44:50.560
of his fathers."" The
equation of the Exilarch

02:44:50.560 --> 02:44:53.360
with King David is rather strong,
as the idea that the Torah comes

02:44:53.360 --> 02:44:56.430
to the Exilarch rather than
vice versa is based on laws

02:44:56.430 --> 02:45:01.200
about passing the Torah scroll to
the Jewish king when one exists.

02:45:01.200 --> 02:45:03.860
Overall, the rabbis did not
seem to particularly object

02:45:03.860 --> 02:45:05.600
to this genealogical claim.

02:45:05.600 --> 02:45:08.790 position:56%
However, they did object to a
similar claim made by another family

02:45:08.790 --> 02:45:10.970
of Babylonian Jewish elites.

02:45:10.970 --> 02:45:13.000
These Jews claimed descent
not from King David,

02:45:13.000 --> 02:45:16.590
but from the Hasmonean kings.

02:45:16.590 --> 02:45:18.610
Thus in the very same
passage in which Rav Yehuda

02:45:18.610 --> 02:45:21.450
and Rav Nahman sparred, we
find the following exchange.

02:45:21.450 --> 02:45:25.580 position:56%
"A certain man from Nehardea entered
a butcher's shop in Pumbeditha

02:45:25.580 --> 02:45:27.880
and demanded, "Give me meat."

02:45:27.880 --> 02:45:30.230
"Wait until Rav Yehuda's attendant
takes his," was the reply,

02:45:30.230 --> 02:45:32.250
"and then we will serve you."

02:45:32.250 --> 02:45:34.880
"Who is Rav Yehuda," he exclaimed,
"to take precedence over me

02:45:34.880 --> 02:45:37.440
and be served before me?"" You're
all probably feeling the same way

02:45:37.440 --> 02:45:38.740
about lunch now.

02:45:38.740 --> 02:45:42.380 position:56%
"When they went and told Rav Yehuda,
he pronounced the ban against him.

02:45:42.380 --> 02:45:43.870
Said they to him, "He" --

02:45:43.870 --> 02:45:45.610
meaning the guy who
claims Hasmonean descent --

02:45:45.610 --> 02:45:47.610
"is wont to call people slaves."

02:45:47.610 --> 02:45:52.120 position:56%
Whereupon Rav Yehuda had him
proclaimed a slave, for Samuel said,

02:45:52.120 --> 02:45:56.600
"With his own blemish he
stigmatizes others as unfit."

02:45:56.600 --> 02:45:59.770
At this stage his opponent said to
Rav Yehuda, "You call me a slave,

02:45:59.770 --> 02:46:02.950
I who am descended from the
royal house of the Hasmoneans?"

02:46:02.950 --> 02:46:05.040
"Thus said Samuel," Rav Yehuda
retorted, "Whoever says,

02:46:05.040 --> 02:46:09.320
"I am descended from the house of
the Hasmoneans is a slave."" A man

02:46:09.320 --> 02:46:10.810
with a particular high estimation

02:46:10.810 --> 02:46:13.140
of himself approaches a
butcher and demands meat.

02:46:13.140 --> 02:46:14.970
The butcher, however,
refuses to sell the man meat

02:46:14.970 --> 02:46:17.620 position:56%
until Rav Yehuda's attendant comes
and takes the first choice of meats,

02:46:17.620 --> 02:46:18.970 position:56%
as a sign of respect for Rav Yehuda.

02:46:18.970 --> 02:46:21.730
The elite man questions how
Rav Yehuda could possibly take

02:46:21.730 --> 02:46:23.140
precedence over him.

02:46:23.140 --> 02:46:24.720
Over the course of the
conversation it is revealed

02:46:24.720 --> 02:46:27.270
that the man claims descent
from the Hasmoneans and,

02:46:27.270 --> 02:46:29.970
like a good patrician, goes around
calling other people slaves.

02:46:29.970 --> 02:46:33.620
Rav Yehuda declares instead that,
in fact, the man is a slave.

02:46:33.620 --> 02:46:36.390
We thus find two different
claims of royal descent

02:46:36.390 --> 02:46:39.550
by two clearly elite-posturing
figures, one from King David

02:46:39.550 --> 02:46:41.230
and one from the Hasmoneans.

02:46:41.230 --> 02:46:43.590
The evidence we have seen until
now suggests that we should --

02:46:43.590 --> 02:46:45.410
we had best look to the
Persian elite context

02:46:45.410 --> 02:46:47.390
to explain this phenomenon.

02:46:47.390 --> 02:46:50.800
And indeed, during the Sasanian
period, royal lineage was, in fact,

02:46:50.800 --> 02:46:52.790
a marker of elite status.

02:46:52.790 --> 02:46:55.400
Throughout this period, many of
the most important elite families,

02:46:55.400 --> 02:46:58.090
as well as kings in Armenia
and Georgia, claimed descent

02:46:58.090 --> 02:47:00.810
from the Arsacids, or
Pahlavi, or Parthian dynasty,

02:47:00.810 --> 02:47:03.100
the dynasty that ruled
before the Sasanians.

02:47:03.100 --> 02:47:07.300
And that's one text that claims it,
and that's a seal from someone --

02:47:07.300 --> 02:47:10.060
an elite who claimed this descent.

02:47:10.060 --> 02:47:12.700
Alongside these were other --
were the other great families,

02:47:12.700 --> 02:47:14.990
some of whom may also have
gone back to the Parthians,

02:47:14.990 --> 02:47:17.810
while others claim
different hoary ancestors.

02:47:17.810 --> 02:47:20.160
The Sasanians themselves
claimed royal descent,

02:47:20.160 --> 02:47:23.320
though the precise history
of this lineage is unclear.

02:47:23.320 --> 02:47:25.510
But by the beginning of the fifth
century, the Sasanians, too,

02:47:25.510 --> 02:47:29.010
adopted a number of strategies
to claim a hoary royal past,

02:47:29.010 --> 02:47:31.430
presumably in part due to
the importance of such claims

02:47:31.430 --> 02:47:32.730
in the Persian world more broadly.

02:47:32.730 --> 02:47:35.550
In this context, then,
it is hardly surprising

02:47:35.550 --> 02:47:38.350
that aspiring Jewish elites
would make parallel claims

02:47:38.350 --> 02:47:40.210
to royal descent.

02:47:40.210 --> 02:47:42.250
Whereas the Exilarch's claim
of genealogical descent

02:47:42.250 --> 02:47:45.280
from King David makes sense given
King David's generally-revered

02:47:45.280 --> 02:47:46.940
status in the Jewish tradition,

02:47:46.940 --> 02:47:51.010
the claim of the Hasmonean descent
is somewhat puzzling, as many Jews,

02:47:51.010 --> 02:47:52.320
and especially the rabbis,

02:47:52.320 --> 02:47:55.380
were at the very least
ambivalent about Hasmonean rule.

02:47:55.380 --> 02:47:57.400
What motivated the man and
his family to claim descent

02:47:57.400 --> 02:47:59.560
from the Hasmoneans
in the first place?

02:47:59.560 --> 02:48:02.140
The answer may lie in the
fact that at the very end

02:48:02.140 --> 02:48:04.620
of the Hasmonean period,
the last king allied himself

02:48:04.620 --> 02:48:06.320
with the Parthians.

02:48:06.320 --> 02:48:08.200
Indeed, this was the
last Hasmonean king,

02:48:08.200 --> 02:48:11.370 position:56%
because despite Parthian assistance,
the Romans and their proxy,

02:48:11.370 --> 02:48:16.080 position:56%
King Herod, ultimately won, bringing
an end to the Hasmonean dynasty.

02:48:16.080 --> 02:48:18.750
I would, therefore, suggest that
some aspiring Jews opted for claims

02:48:18.750 --> 02:48:20.600
of descent from Jewish
kings who had a history

02:48:20.600 --> 02:48:23.950
of allying themselves
with Persian rulers.

02:48:23.950 --> 02:48:26.380
Moreover, in this context, the
habit of the Hasmonean descendent

02:48:26.380 --> 02:48:28.650
to call others slaves
makes more sense.

02:48:28.650 --> 02:48:30.830
A slave in Sasanian law
was the opposite of someone

02:48:30.830 --> 02:48:33.170
with untainted royal
genealogical descent.

02:48:33.170 --> 02:48:35.280
Slaves could be married off
at the whim of the owner,

02:48:35.280 --> 02:48:38.450
and the children were
then his slaves as well.

02:48:38.450 --> 02:48:39.750
Indeed, we find a striking source

02:48:39.750 --> 02:48:42.770
that discusses precisely how some
Iranians claiming Parthian descent

02:48:42.770 --> 02:48:44.220
were reduced to slaves.

02:48:44.220 --> 02:48:45.670
That's the source over there.

02:48:45.670 --> 02:48:50.460
Thus, the Exilarch, and presumably
other elite Jewish families

02:48:50.460 --> 02:48:53.370
like the Jew who claimed Hasmonean
descent, adopted a wide range

02:48:53.370 --> 02:48:55.430
of trappings of Persian nobility.

02:48:55.430 --> 02:48:56.810
They used specialized
Persian language,

02:48:56.810 --> 02:48:58.750
adopted Persian mores
regarding women,

02:48:58.750 --> 02:49:00.540 position:56%
and like their elite Sasanian peers,

02:49:00.540 --> 02:49:03.190
maintained royal genealogical
claims.

02:49:03.190 --> 02:49:04.490
Did it work?

02:49:04.490 --> 02:49:06.740
Were at least some of these
Jews successful in integrating

02:49:06.740 --> 02:49:08.850
into the Sasanian elite class?

02:49:08.850 --> 02:49:12.040 position:56%
In the case of the Exilarch, the
answer seems to be a definitive yes,

02:49:12.040 --> 02:49:14.540
as seen from the only non-rabbinic
source to mention the Exilarch,

02:49:14.540 --> 02:49:18.060
which was edited and translated
by our own Touraj Daryaee.

02:49:18.060 --> 02:49:21.640
And I'm reading here, "The city
of Susa and Sustar were built

02:49:21.640 --> 02:49:24.920
by Sisinduxt, the wife of
Yazdigird, the sun of Sabuhr,

02:49:24.920 --> 02:49:28.590
since she was the daughter of the
Exilarch, the King of the Jews,

02:49:28.590 --> 02:49:30.220
and also was the mother
of Wahram Gor."

02:49:30.220 --> 02:49:32.490
According to this source,

02:49:32.490 --> 02:49:36.180 position:56%
the Sasanian king Yazdgird I married
the daughter of the Jewish Exilarch.

02:49:36.180 --> 02:49:38.390
Like Danog, the daughter
of Rav Nahman,

02:49:38.390 --> 02:49:40.850
the daughter of the Exilarch
here receives a nice Persian name

02:49:40.850 --> 02:49:42.820
of Daughter of Susa.

02:49:42.820 --> 02:49:44.300
What's especially important here is

02:49:44.300 --> 02:49:47.730
that the Exilarch is identified
as the King of the Jews.

02:49:47.730 --> 02:49:50.640
This is not a mere expression, as
every other figure in this text

02:49:50.640 --> 02:49:54.900
who is called a shah refers to
a historical or mythical king.

02:49:54.900 --> 02:49:57.290
I would suggest that this claim --
that the claim of Davidic descent

02:49:57.290 --> 02:50:00.530
by the Exilarch was accepted by
the Sasanian royal household.

02:50:00.530 --> 02:50:01.830
This would also explain
how the daughter

02:50:01.830 --> 02:50:04.260
of the Exilarch was found
worthy to marry the king,

02:50:04.260 --> 02:50:07.420
as Sasanian kings only married
daughters of kings or noblemen.

02:50:07.420 --> 02:50:12.170
An example would be Shirin, as
Scott's presentation just showed.

02:50:12.170 --> 02:50:13.470
I end with the rabbis.

02:50:13.470 --> 02:50:16.990 position:56%
What do we make of rabbinic
disapproval of at least some aspects

02:50:16.990 --> 02:50:19.120
of these elite Jewish families?

02:50:19.120 --> 02:50:22.160
Some have suggested that this
shows a resistance by some rabbis

02:50:22.160 --> 02:50:24.210
to Persian norms in general.

02:50:24.210 --> 02:50:26.180
However, I think this is incorrect.

02:50:26.180 --> 02:50:28.680
Instead, I would argue that the
rabbis' disapproved of the Exilarch

02:50:28.680 --> 02:50:31.670 position:56%
and the purported Hasmonean
descendent because the latter strove

02:50:31.670 --> 02:50:34.870
to be part of elite Persian
society, whereas the rabbis strove

02:50:34.870 --> 02:50:37.320
to be elites in their
own local Jewish society.

02:50:37.320 --> 02:50:41.820
Thus, if we return to the story
of Rav Yehuda and Rav Nahman

02:50:41.820 --> 02:50:43.910
where Rav Yehuda critiqued Rav
Nahman for using Middle Persian

02:50:43.910 --> 02:50:46.970
and Greek words, we see that
the words Rav Yehuda preferred,

02:50:46.970 --> 02:50:49.660
the words he attributed to
the rabbis or common-folk,

02:50:49.660 --> 02:50:52.100
are themselves often
Persian and Greek words.

02:50:52.100 --> 02:50:54.830
And these are all the
highlighted words.

02:50:54.830 --> 02:50:58.380
However, there is an important
difference between these words.

02:50:58.380 --> 02:51:00.100
Rav Nahman's vocabulary
included terms

02:51:00.100 --> 02:51:02.490
that were relatively new
to the Sasanian period.

02:51:02.490 --> 02:51:03.870
Thus, they are either
Middle Persian words

02:51:03.870 --> 02:51:06.600
or Greek words never
attested before.

02:51:06.600 --> 02:51:08.680
By contrast, the words of
the rabbis or the words

02:51:08.680 --> 02:51:10.860
of the common-folk were
either Parthian or Greek words

02:51:10.860 --> 02:51:13.520
that were introduced into Jewish
Aramaic in an earlier period.

02:51:13.520 --> 02:51:16.530
In linguistic parlance, this
is -- they were retentions.

02:51:16.530 --> 02:51:19.560 position:56%
In other words, the rabbis are not
opposed to Persian or Greek, per se.

02:51:19.560 --> 02:51:22.070
They are opposed to new
words and terminology

02:51:22.070 --> 02:51:26.390 position:56%
which they considered haughty,
apparently signs of Persian elitism.

02:51:26.390 --> 02:51:30.200
But this isn't opposition to
elite Persian norms as such.

02:51:30.200 --> 02:51:33.070
In fact, the Babylonian rabbis seem
to have modeled their own academies

02:51:33.070 --> 02:51:34.760 position:56%
after royal or elite Persian courts.

02:51:34.760 --> 02:51:38.810
For example, the Babylonian
academies were seated in rows just

02:51:38.810 --> 02:51:40.220
like the royal Persian court.

02:51:40.220 --> 02:51:44.040
And in the first section here
you see how a rabbi is demoted

02:51:44.040 --> 02:51:48.440
or promoted up the seven rows based
on how clever his questions are.

02:51:48.440 --> 02:51:52.230 position:56%
And the bottom, another rabbi who
he's asking questions to is promoted

02:51:52.230 --> 02:51:56.770 position:56%
and demoted with cushions, depending
on how good his answers are.

02:51:56.770 --> 02:52:00.960
So for example, the Babylonian
academies were seated in rows,

02:52:00.960 --> 02:52:03.900
just like the royal Persian court.

02:52:03.900 --> 02:52:06.270
Indeed, sitting in rows
seems to have been central

02:52:06.270 --> 02:52:08.090
to Persian imperial
culture for centuries,

02:52:08.090 --> 02:52:10.770
as Ancient Greek authors report
that Cyrus' court sat in rows,

02:52:10.770 --> 02:52:12.260 position:56%
and the Arsacids adopted this aspect

02:52:12.260 --> 02:52:15.040
of imperial Persian
culture themselves.

02:52:15.040 --> 02:52:18.190
Similarly, the prestigious
leading members of the academy sat

02:52:18.190 --> 02:52:20.380
on a number of cushions
that delineated their rank,

02:52:20.380 --> 02:52:21.680
also like the royal Persian court.

02:52:21.680 --> 02:52:25.330
Both the tows and the
cushions are standard aspects

02:52:25.330 --> 02:52:26.660
of Persian noble culture.

02:52:26.660 --> 02:52:29.540
In fact, if one thinks
about Rav Yehuda's encounter

02:52:29.540 --> 02:52:32.530
with the Hasmonean descendent,
their dispute did not simply arise

02:52:32.530 --> 02:52:35.270
because the Hasmonean
man acted as an elite,

02:52:35.270 --> 02:52:37.840
but precisely because the
Hasmonean man claimed superiority

02:52:37.840 --> 02:52:40.830
to Rav Yehuda's own privileged
position to choose his meats first.

02:52:40.830 --> 02:52:44.190
Rav Yehuda may have been less
opposed to elitism as such

02:52:44.190 --> 02:52:47.480
than to elitism that infringed
on his own privileges.

02:52:47.480 --> 02:52:49.460
Indeed, Rav Yehuda
calls the man a slave

02:52:49.460 --> 02:52:50.950
because the man called
others slaves,

02:52:50.950 --> 02:52:53.560
but by declaring the Hasmonean
descendent to be a slave,

02:52:53.560 --> 02:52:58.070
wouldn't Rav Yehuda be
committing the same offense?

02:52:58.070 --> 02:53:01.010 position:56%
Jews of all stripes were Persianized
and adopted the trappings

02:53:01.010 --> 02:53:02.660
of Persian culture and status.

02:53:02.660 --> 02:53:05.720
This is true of Jews throughout the
various Persian periods, as seen,

02:53:05.720 --> 02:53:07.770
for instance, by comparing
the architecture of Jewish

02:53:07.770 --> 02:53:10.360
and Muslim [inaudible]
shrines from the 18th century.

02:53:10.360 --> 02:53:12.660
But what exactly did
Persianization look like?

02:53:12.660 --> 02:53:15.830
And how exactly different Jews
adopt, reject, contest, co-op,

02:53:15.830 --> 02:53:18.490
and even contribute to Persian
culture and society changes

02:53:18.490 --> 02:53:22.270
with time, as does the
significance of Persianization.

02:53:22.270 --> 02:53:26.010
In the Sasanian period some
Jews, like the Exilarch,

02:53:26.010 --> 02:53:29.600 position:56%
strove to join elite Persian society
while others, like the rabbis,

02:53:29.600 --> 02:53:32.320
imagined their own academies
as elite courts and themselves

02:53:32.320 --> 02:53:34.360
as worthy of elite privileges.

02:53:34.360 --> 02:53:37.030
Persianization was not simply
something external to Jews,

02:53:37.030 --> 02:53:39.430
a set of cultural practices
they at times adopted

02:53:39.430 --> 02:53:41.320
and at other times rejected.

02:53:41.320 --> 02:53:44.760
Persianization inevitably affected
Jews living in the Sasanian period,

02:53:44.760 --> 02:53:46.890
their self-understanding,
aspirations, and more.

02:53:46.890 --> 02:53:50.310
It is my hope that future research
will help us appreciate how crucial

02:53:50.310 --> 02:53:53.080 position:56%
the Sasanian period was for these
Jews in particular and, as a result,

02:53:53.080 --> 02:53:54.700
for Jewish history more broadly.

