03:16:34.840 --> 03:16:38.690
that the Sasanian society
experienced different ranges

03:16:38.690 --> 03:16:43.020
of the writing culture from
the memorial function of royal

03:16:43.020 --> 03:16:46.850
or aristocratic lapidary
inscriptions,

03:16:46.850 --> 03:16:50.470
up to the more practical, but
still specialized activities

03:16:50.470 --> 03:16:56.260
of the scribes in court and
provincial administrative networks.

03:16:56.260 --> 03:16:59.780
Besides, their vernacular
language, per se,

03:16:59.780 --> 03:17:03.210
equals as we say Middle
Persian or Pahlavi,

03:17:03.210 --> 03:17:06.780
seems to possess all the
features of a literary language.

03:17:06.780 --> 03:17:11.740
It has a simple morphology
but a remarkable flexibility

03:17:11.740 --> 03:17:17.990
and an internal dynamism that makes
word composition very productive.

03:17:21.630 --> 03:17:30.030 position:56%
Despite this rich and indispensable
tool for expression, our information

03:17:30.030 --> 03:17:33.580
about books in the Sasanian
period is very limited.

03:17:33.580 --> 03:17:36.840
Of course, we have no reason
to doubt that the compilation

03:17:36.840 --> 03:17:40.420 position:56%
and edition of the very famous
"Xwaday-Namag," the "Book of Kings,"

03:17:40.420 --> 03:17:42.940
that we know only by its
title and some outlines,

03:17:42.940 --> 03:17:47.160
were directly supervised by
the king or his chancellery.

03:17:47.160 --> 03:17:50.060
We also know that different
aspects of the courtly customs,

03:17:50.060 --> 03:17:53.890
like protocol of audience
and banqueting,

03:17:53.890 --> 03:17:58.060
were confined in special volumes
like "Ewen-Namag" or "Gah-Namag,"

03:17:58.060 --> 03:18:00.450
of which we know very little.

03:18:00.450 --> 03:18:05.700
If Sasanian didn't produce many
books, at least they liked them.

03:18:05.700 --> 03:18:09.770
They had, for instance, Indian
parables, Indian legends translated

03:18:09.770 --> 03:18:12.270
into Middle Persian as
the "Kalilag ud Dimnag"

03:18:12.270 --> 03:18:14.210
from the Sanskrit "Panchatantra."

03:18:14.210 --> 03:18:17.900
Or their -- the Sasanian
like to be offered ones.

03:18:17.900 --> 03:18:21.150
The prophet Mani wrote
"Shapuragan" for the King of Kings.

03:18:21.150 --> 03:18:25.570
And also Priscianus of Lydia,
one of the last Neoplatonists,

03:18:25.570 --> 03:18:29.700
who was forced to seek
asylum in the Sasanian court,

03:18:29.700 --> 03:18:35.230
offered his "Soluciones"
to Khosrow I.

03:18:35.230 --> 03:18:39.790
One field only seems to have
been reluctant for a while

03:18:39.790 --> 03:18:42.840
to the writing culture, probably
because it didn't need it,

03:18:42.840 --> 03:18:47.970
or it found idols scriptures, or
the act of writing undeserving

03:18:47.970 --> 03:18:52.540
of its own status, or perhaps
it considered writing prone

03:18:52.540 --> 03:18:54.500
to alteration, and therefore,

03:18:54.500 --> 03:18:58.120
not suitable for a
long-lasting tradition.

03:18:58.120 --> 03:19:00.710
I am, of course, pointing
to the sacred knowledge

03:19:00.710 --> 03:19:04.430
of Zoroastrian priests who
considered their own memory

03:19:04.430 --> 03:19:10.630
as the only worthy keeper of
the holy words of the "Avesta."

03:19:10.630 --> 03:19:14.060
Even if we agree with the
hypothesis that the translations

03:19:14.060 --> 03:19:16.940
and commentaries of the
"Avesta" could have been put

03:19:16.940 --> 03:19:20.170
down into writing before
the Sasanian period.

03:19:20.170 --> 03:19:23.180
For paleographical reasons
we are quite certain

03:19:23.180 --> 03:19:26.050
that it wasn't the case
for the "Avesta" itself.

03:19:26.050 --> 03:19:29.660
Most scholars agree that after many
centuries of oral transmission,

03:19:29.660 --> 03:19:32.830
the "Avesta" was written for the
first time in the second half

03:19:32.830 --> 03:19:35.060
of the sixth century
A.D. at the time

03:19:35.060 --> 03:19:39.080
of the Sasanian King Khosrow
I even though it continued

03:19:39.080 --> 03:19:42.450
to be taught orally, memorized,
and recited by priests,

03:19:42.450 --> 03:19:46.460
especially by ones involved
in the ritual activities

03:19:46.460 --> 03:19:49.200
or in the educational activities.

03:19:50.700 --> 03:19:53.670
Writing down the "Avesta"
didn't happen in one day.

03:19:53.670 --> 03:19:57.040
It needed a long process,
and priestly gatherings,

03:19:57.040 --> 03:19:59.920
priests who were experts
in the pronunciation

03:19:59.920 --> 03:20:03.170
of the liturgical hymns,
specialists of phonetics,

03:20:03.170 --> 03:20:06.960
and also of paleography because
they had to invent a new alphabet

03:20:06.960 --> 03:20:11.350 position:56%
in order to write down the holy text
as precisely as possible and turn it

03:20:11.350 --> 03:20:13.690
into a holy book, as
Jews, Christians,

03:20:13.690 --> 03:20:16.410
Manichaeans possessed
one long before them.

03:20:16.410 --> 03:20:20.350
This radical innovation --
let's say a revolution --

03:20:20.350 --> 03:20:23.540
in their religious tradition
was not well-welcomed --

03:20:23.540 --> 03:20:24.930
was not welcomed by all.

03:20:24.930 --> 03:20:29.210
But it probably stimulated

03:20:29.210 --> 03:20:33.440
and [inaudible] the status
of religious writing.

03:20:33.440 --> 03:20:36.680
The priestly class began
to have an easier access

03:20:36.680 --> 03:20:41.620 position:56%
to scientific knowledge, astrology,
medicine, geometry, botany, zoology.

03:20:41.620 --> 03:20:44.510
And they sometimes
incorporated their material

03:20:44.510 --> 03:20:46.780
into their religious writings.

03:20:46.780 --> 03:20:50.090
The scholar priest seems
to have a remarkable skill

03:20:50.090 --> 03:20:54.520
to describe the word from the
very beginning of the creation

03:20:54.520 --> 03:20:57.990
to the fresh-geared order
renovation at the end of time.

03:20:57.990 --> 03:21:02.330 position:56%
And scientific observation makes
their enumeration even more accurate

03:21:02.330 --> 03:21:04.590
and believable.

03:21:04.590 --> 03:21:07.300
By contacts with different
communities, for instance,

03:21:07.300 --> 03:21:10.190
in the milieu of the
Academy of Gondishapur,

03:21:10.190 --> 03:21:12.180
their writings were
surely influenced

03:21:12.180 --> 03:21:17.830
by the intellectual effervescence
of the late Sasanian period

03:21:17.830 --> 03:21:21.970
and beyond it in the court of the
Caliph of Baghdad, for instance,

03:21:21.970 --> 03:21:24.780
where the heads of the
Zoroastrian community were active

03:21:24.780 --> 03:21:26.400
up to the tenth century.

03:21:26.400 --> 03:21:32.010
Of this literary production,
only a restricted amount

03:21:32.010 --> 03:21:35.520
of text has been transmitted to us.

03:21:35.520 --> 03:21:37.500
That is what we call
the Pahlavi books,

03:21:37.500 --> 03:21:40.240
or Zoroastrian Middle Persian
text, that we know only

03:21:40.240 --> 03:21:46.690
from medieval manuscripts, the
oldest preserved one dated to 1322.

03:21:46.690 --> 03:21:49.580
Despite important efforts
of generational scholars

03:21:49.580 --> 03:21:52.390
and some colleagues
here in this room,

03:21:52.390 --> 03:21:56.270
this Middle Persian literature
remains incompletely edited

03:21:56.270 --> 03:21:57.800
or commented on.

03:21:57.800 --> 03:21:59.580
The question we may ask is

03:21:59.580 --> 03:22:05.580
to what extent does this corpus
inform us about the Sasanians?

03:22:05.580 --> 03:22:09.350
How a corpus postdated to
this period and written

03:22:09.350 --> 03:22:13.580
by Zoroastrian priests for
Zoroastrian priests may be relevant

03:22:13.580 --> 03:22:16.360
as a source of Sasanian time?

03:22:16.360 --> 03:22:20.750
On this last point, the French
Iranist Philippe Gignoux,

03:22:20.750 --> 03:22:23.990
who devoted many of his works
to the Middle Persian documents

03:22:23.990 --> 03:22:27.100
and Sasanian history,
claimed in the last '70s

03:22:27.100 --> 03:22:30.840
that this text must be
seen as secondary sources,

03:22:30.840 --> 03:22:32.610
and because of their
chronology, they my less --

03:22:32.610 --> 03:22:36.020
they are less important
than coins and seals.

03:22:36.020 --> 03:22:40.240
More recently, another outstanding
historian, Albert de Jong,

03:22:40.240 --> 03:22:43.730
argued that we have no reliable
techniques and no methods

03:22:43.730 --> 03:22:45.400
to separate Sasanian material

03:22:45.400 --> 03:22:48.230
from post-Sasanian
material and Pahlavi books.

03:22:48.230 --> 03:22:53.860
And he also notes that the
authors of this text are, I quote,

03:22:53.860 --> 03:22:58.880
"remarkably free from nostalgia and
remarkably diffident in the memory

03:22:58.880 --> 03:23:02.630
of the Sasanians, who are by no
means generally seen as heroes

03:23:02.630 --> 03:23:04.890
of the religion," end of quote.

03:23:04.890 --> 03:23:11.880 position:56%
I think that some of this
assessment might need to be amended,

03:23:11.880 --> 03:23:15.940
though I myself admit and deplore
the lack of coherent methodology

03:23:15.940 --> 03:23:18.090
and reliable techniques used to --

03:23:18.090 --> 03:23:21.730
so far regarding the
chronology of this text.

03:23:21.730 --> 03:23:24.670
At this point I would like
to suggest not a technique --

03:23:24.670 --> 03:23:28.140
I have none -- but
rather a new perspective

03:23:28.140 --> 03:23:30.380
to analyze some Middle
Persian narrations

03:23:30.380 --> 03:23:32.780
that could provide
essential elements not only

03:23:32.780 --> 03:23:35.480
to the understanding of
interconnection between narration

03:23:35.480 --> 03:23:38.830
and political propaganda
in the late Sasanian time,

03:23:38.830 --> 03:23:42.370
but also to re-evaluate the
place of the Sasanian king

03:23:42.370 --> 03:23:45.080
within the Zoroastrian
myth ideology.

03:23:45.080 --> 03:23:55.520 position:56%
