03:24:01.140 --> 03:24:06.580
and a page -- a young aristocrat.

03:24:06.580 --> 03:24:12.440
This dialogical form involving
Khosrow I and a knowledgeable man,

03:24:12.440 --> 03:24:16.710
whoever he might be, was a very
common genre in this period.

03:24:16.710 --> 03:24:19.990
We have the Latin translation
of the Neoplatonist Christian

03:24:19.990 --> 03:24:23.900
and his answers to King Khosrow
that I mentioned earlier,

03:24:23.900 --> 03:24:28.210
or even a late Arabic
parallels it in [speaking

03:24:28.210 --> 03:24:30.600
in foreign language]
of the ninth century.

03:24:30.600 --> 03:24:38.520
Here is the frame story of the
"Husraw I Kawadan Ud Radag,"

03:24:38.520 --> 03:24:39.920
this Middle Persian text.

03:24:39.920 --> 03:24:41.390
The plot is extremely simple.

03:24:41.390 --> 03:24:44.810
I hope you can read the screen,
otherwise I can read it for you.

03:24:44.810 --> 03:24:49.090
"A young aristocrat has
been deprived from his rank

03:24:49.090 --> 03:24:51.450
and has lost his fortune.

03:24:51.450 --> 03:24:56.610 position:56%
He requests a hearing, stands before
the king," and this gesture imposed

03:24:56.610 --> 03:25:00.840
by the protocol, as we see in
this detail of a silver dish,

03:25:00.840 --> 03:25:05.490
where the king does not wear
the same crown as Khosrow I,

03:25:05.490 --> 03:25:07.550
but it is Khosrow anyway.

03:25:07.550 --> 03:25:11.130 position:56%
And the page tried to gain the favor
and the protection of the king.

03:25:11.130 --> 03:25:15.980
For achieving that, he describes
in detail his education,

03:25:15.980 --> 03:25:20.140
which fits exactly the standards
of aristocratic Sasanian military

03:25:20.140 --> 03:25:24.820
and intellectual training,
including religious education,

03:25:24.820 --> 03:25:27.220
astrological knowledge,
and also training

03:25:27.220 --> 03:25:31.150
in games like chess and polo.

03:25:31.150 --> 03:25:35.520
Then beings the questioning.

03:25:35.520 --> 03:25:38.960
The king wants to know what
is the best of everything

03:25:38.960 --> 03:25:46.220
in the servant's eye, including
food, wine, music, perfumes,

03:25:46.220 --> 03:25:49.980
women, horses, and so on.

03:25:49.980 --> 03:25:55.390
The answer gives rise to a long
enumeration of the realia of the --

03:25:55.390 --> 03:25:59.740 position:56%
and the material culture of Sasanian
Iran and the courtier protocol.

03:25:59.740 --> 03:26:05.790
When some place names are
mentioned, as it is the case

03:26:05.790 --> 03:26:10.850 position:56%
with the great varieties for the
most excellent wines, we can observe

03:26:10.850 --> 03:26:13.750
that these regions are, in
fact, included in the border

03:26:13.750 --> 03:26:16.550
of the Sasanian realm at
the time of Khosrow I.

03:26:16.550 --> 03:26:20.920
This detail shows that the
period of the composition

03:26:20.920 --> 03:26:25.880
of the text is very likely to
be the period of his reign.

03:26:25.880 --> 03:26:27.460
And this is -- that is
-- that it was not --

03:26:27.460 --> 03:26:30.980
the story was not attributed
to him retrospectively,

03:26:30.980 --> 03:26:33.080
as it was presumably assumed.

03:26:33.080 --> 03:26:41.230
But this is not the only result of
reliable techniques of observation.

03:26:41.230 --> 03:26:46.370
The king is satisfied by the
answer of the young page,

03:26:46.370 --> 03:26:50.800
and he bestows a high military
title of the marzban on him.

03:26:50.800 --> 03:26:53.440
Then the page finds
himself in situations

03:26:53.440 --> 03:26:54.740
where he has to prove his courage.

03:26:54.740 --> 03:26:59.510
He captures dangerous lions, and
he has to prove also his chastity.

03:26:59.510 --> 03:27:01.880
And when he passes these
ordeals, the king decides

03:27:01.880 --> 03:27:03.430
to keep him at the court.

03:27:03.430 --> 03:27:05.220
End of the story.

03:27:05.220 --> 03:27:10.320
Now what is the moral of the social
ascension of an anonymous servant?

03:27:10.320 --> 03:27:14.030
What could be significance for
the audience of the sixth century?

03:27:14.030 --> 03:27:20.230
It seems to be that behind this
naive court story hides a strong

03:27:20.230 --> 03:27:21.530
political propaganda.

03:27:21.530 --> 03:27:27.500
This Middle Persian Text only makes
sense if we consider the context

03:27:27.500 --> 03:27:30.920
of internal policy according
to which it was composed.

03:27:30.920 --> 03:27:34.990
Khosrow I, at the beginning of his
reign, had to face the consequences

03:27:34.990 --> 03:27:37.430
of a socioeconomic
crisis that started

03:27:37.430 --> 03:27:40.620
in the time of his father Kavadh.

03:27:40.620 --> 03:27:44.110
Khodadad mentioned the
story this morning.

03:27:44.110 --> 03:27:48.900
Kavadh actually supported a
religious leader called Mazdak

03:27:48.900 --> 03:27:52.070
because he found Mazdakism
a useful instrument

03:27:52.070 --> 03:27:54.930
for undermining the
power of the clergy.

03:27:54.930 --> 03:27:57.810
The Mazdak movement might have
attracted the lower classes

03:27:57.810 --> 03:28:01.510
of the society.

03:28:01.510 --> 03:28:05.390 position:56%
I don't have time to go into details
about the social and moral doctrine,

03:28:05.390 --> 03:28:10.590
but from the Zoroastrian point
of view it was seen not only

03:28:10.590 --> 03:28:15.900
as a dangerous heresy, but
also as an economic disaster

03:28:15.900 --> 03:28:18.330
that would explain why
the story of the --

03:28:18.330 --> 03:28:21.080
in this story, the page
has lost his fortune

03:28:21.080 --> 03:28:23.980
and turns to the court for help.

03:28:23.980 --> 03:28:29.400
Here as well as in other stories,
Khosrow I took the occasion

03:28:29.400 --> 03:28:33.210
of presenting himself as the
champion of anti-Mazdakism.

03:28:33.210 --> 03:28:38.580
In fact, Khosrow I is very
well-known for his reforms.

03:28:38.580 --> 03:28:41.980
He actually continued to
[inaudible] economic reforms

03:28:41.980 --> 03:28:45.640
that his father initiated,
and a better control

03:28:45.640 --> 03:28:49.980
over the agricultural production,
and a taxes levy required

03:28:49.980 --> 03:28:53.450
to rebalance the social forces.

03:28:53.450 --> 03:28:57.670
The power of the great noble
houses needed to be reduced,

03:28:57.670 --> 03:29:03.010
and instead the king favored
the small land-holding gentry.

03:29:03.010 --> 03:29:07.520 position:56%
It is clear to me that the depiction
of the politically-correct figure

03:29:07.520 --> 03:29:11.410
of the young page in this story
echoes the increased confidence

03:29:11.410 --> 03:29:15.740 position:56%
of the king toward the lesser
nobility, here presented as a victim

03:29:15.740 --> 03:29:20.310
of Mazdak economic project,
or its alleged communism.

03:29:20.310 --> 03:29:22.900
And this story is,
therefore, better understood

03:29:22.900 --> 03:29:31.850 position:56%
in the social reconstruction context
of the post-Mazdakite crisis.

03:29:31.850 --> 03:29:37.040
Allow me now to present another
brief example of the depiction

03:29:37.040 --> 03:29:40.520
of the Sasanian king as
a hero of the religion,

03:29:40.520 --> 03:29:44.450
as I don't find Middle Persian
Zoroastrian literature particularly

03:29:44.450 --> 03:29:46.950
diffident to the memory
of the kings.

03:29:46.950 --> 03:29:50.010
Quite on the contrary,
it keeps telling us

03:29:50.010 --> 03:29:52.950
that the Zoroastrian
tradition has been transmitted

03:29:52.950 --> 03:29:56.960
from immemorial times
along with Iranian kings,

03:29:56.960 --> 03:29:59.660
and especially thanks
to the Sasanian kings.

03:29:59.660 --> 03:30:02.610
Not all of them, of course,
but at least three or four

03:30:02.610 --> 03:30:04.330
of the most important ones.

03:30:04.330 --> 03:30:08.600
I don't want to bother you
with the details of the text,

03:30:08.600 --> 03:30:12.980
and this sketch will surely be
enough to illustrate the case.

03:30:12.980 --> 03:30:17.010
This is what we find -- this
chart is what we find in --

03:30:17.010 --> 03:30:21.880
or we can reconstruct after
many Middle Persian texts,

03:30:21.880 --> 03:30:25.590
especially the "Denkard
IV," an Arabic text based

03:30:25.590 --> 03:30:29.030
on earlier Middle Persian texts.

03:30:29.030 --> 03:30:33.280
The genealogical table
of the Iranian royalty

03:30:33.280 --> 03:30:38.630
in which the Sasanians
present themselves as the heirs

03:30:38.630 --> 03:30:45.830
of the legendary Kayanid dynasty,
here represented by Wishtasp.

03:30:45.830 --> 03:30:49.950
This legacy is not a mere
historical resonance,

03:30:49.950 --> 03:30:52.980
nor an intellectual construct.

03:30:52.980 --> 03:30:58.000
It has to be sustained by
tangible elements and facts.

03:30:58.000 --> 03:31:01.460
This transmission process
could apply to many things,

03:31:01.460 --> 03:31:05.380
the empire itself might be
handed down through generations,

03:31:05.380 --> 03:31:07.820
or the [speaking in foreign
language], the royal glory.

03:31:07.820 --> 03:31:12.450
But I choose to show you the myth

03:31:12.450 --> 03:31:14.600
of the transmission of
the holy scriptures.

03:31:14.600 --> 03:31:18.780
As you can see here, if you live
in the sixth century and you want

03:31:18.780 --> 03:31:22.040
to write a good story,
before you post it

03:31:22.040 --> 03:31:25.140
on the sixth century
Facebook, which is, of course,

03:31:25.140 --> 03:31:28.070
the network of the
mythical narrations

03:31:28.070 --> 03:31:31.960
that were spread throughout
the priestly schools,

03:31:31.960 --> 03:31:35.600
or the festive gatherings,
or whatever.

03:31:35.600 --> 03:31:39.520
But your story has to
meet established criteria

03:31:39.520 --> 03:31:44.230
of the Zoroastrian mythology to
be considered as a good story.

03:31:44.230 --> 03:31:46.240
Here is some of this criteria.

03:31:46.240 --> 03:31:50.070
The story has to fit the general
picture of the mythical chronology,

03:31:50.070 --> 03:31:56.620
the scheme of the succession of
millennia with different periods,

03:31:56.620 --> 03:31:59.370
dynasties, and reigns, and so on.

03:31:59.370 --> 03:32:05.060
The second criteria is the presence
of three characters, the hero --

03:32:05.060 --> 03:32:10.790
here a king -- the sage or the
wise man, most of the time a magus,

03:32:10.790 --> 03:32:15.930
and a common enemy [inaudible]
tied to Iran and its religion.

03:32:15.930 --> 03:32:20.130
You also need something that links
the generation one to the other.

03:32:20.130 --> 03:32:23.490
According to this version of the
myth, the transmitted element

03:32:23.490 --> 03:32:27.330
from the Kayanid to
Sasanian was the "Avesta,"

03:32:27.330 --> 03:32:33.920 position:56%
not as the liturgical recitation nor
as the vague notion named the Den,

03:32:33.920 --> 03:32:39.600
but as a real object,
as a book handed down,

03:32:39.600 --> 03:32:41.970
after self-vicissitudes,
of course --

03:32:41.970 --> 03:32:45.640
Alexandre was there --
to the Sasanian kings.

03:32:45.640 --> 03:32:50.270
And each of them has contributed
to its edition, copying,

03:32:50.270 --> 03:32:51.880
reassembling, and completing.

03:32:51.880 --> 03:32:58.860
When you want to legitimize
the existence of something,

03:32:58.860 --> 03:33:02.630
basically you only need to
say that it was here before.

03:33:02.630 --> 03:33:04.170
"My ancestors gave it to me,

03:33:04.170 --> 03:33:08.140
so there is no reason
to doubt about it."

03:33:08.140 --> 03:33:14.030
This raises another question, why
does the author of this text need

03:33:14.030 --> 03:33:20.010
to legitimize the existence
of the "Avesta" as a book?

03:33:20.010 --> 03:33:23.080
The answer is clear, it
wasn't a book before it.

03:33:23.080 --> 03:33:29.830
It seems to me that this narration
is only meant to place Khosrow I

03:33:29.830 --> 03:33:35.070
at the end of this line as
the legitimate depository

03:33:35.070 --> 03:33:38.330
and heroic savior of the holy book,

03:33:38.330 --> 03:33:41.290
which has accumulated all
the knowledge of the time

03:33:41.290 --> 03:33:44.960
and has become the epitome
of the scions of the Iranian

03:33:44.960 --> 03:33:51.320
and non-Iranian world, and that it
has a distinctive shape of a codex

03:33:51.320 --> 03:33:55.250
or a book, [speaking in foreign
language] in Middle Persian.

03:33:55.250 --> 03:33:58.230
This holistic and cosmic
aspect of the

03:33:58.230 --> 03:34:00.520
"Avesta" truly reminds the holistic

03:34:00.520 --> 03:34:03.970
and cosmic aspect of
the king himself.

03:34:03.970 --> 03:34:09.750
I hope these two tiny examples
were enough to demonstrate

03:34:09.750 --> 03:34:13.630
that the Middle Persian literature
has not yet said its last word

03:34:13.630 --> 03:34:17.660
about the Sasanian kings,
and that it is not surprising

03:34:17.660 --> 03:34:22.530
that profound historical and social
transformations have left a trace

03:34:22.530 --> 03:34:26.500
into the highly-conservative and
faithfully-transmitted tradition,

03:34:26.500 --> 03:34:30.640
if we are inclined of using new
techniques to look for them.

03:34:30.640 --> 03:34:32.440
Thank you.

03:34:32.440 --> 03:34:42.640
[ Applause ]

03:34:42.640 --> 03:34:45.890
