&gt;&gt; Judith Lerner.

03:36:06.380 --> 03:36:07.680
Thank you very much, Hirad.

03:36:07.680 --> 03:36:09.150
And thank you all for coming.

03:36:09.150 --> 03:36:11.190
And thanks to all the people

03:36:11.190 --> 03:36:17.340
who have made this fascinating
gathering possible today.

03:36:17.340 --> 03:36:20.770
I am particularly grateful
for this opportunity to talk

03:36:20.770 --> 03:36:26.760
about an important aspect of the
art created under the Qajar dynasty

03:36:26.760 --> 03:36:32.190
that ruled Persia from the late
18th to the early 20th century.

03:36:32.190 --> 03:36:35.800
This is the art of
carving into living rock,

03:36:35.800 --> 03:36:41.530
that is a large boulder or, more
typically, a cliff or mountainside,

03:36:41.530 --> 03:36:45.560 position:56%
of monumental images in high relief.

03:36:45.560 --> 03:36:47.680
This form of visual art is one

03:36:47.680 --> 03:36:51.420
of several artistic
innovations of the Qajar period.

03:36:51.420 --> 03:36:58.890 position:56%
It seems to have been the brainchild
of -- let's see if this works --

03:36:58.890 --> 03:37:04.970
of Fath-Ali Shah, the
second Qajar ruler.

03:37:04.970 --> 03:37:07.770
Although, in his extensive
use of it,

03:37:07.770 --> 03:37:13.130
he was actually revisiting
an artistic medium that began

03:37:13.130 --> 03:37:16.260
in very ancient, pre-Islamic times.

03:37:16.260 --> 03:37:20.860
And I'm sure many of you are
familiar with the Qajars,

03:37:20.860 --> 03:37:23.040
and particularly Fath-Ali Shah.

03:37:23.040 --> 03:37:26.730
And this is a particularly
wonderful -- he was rather vain,

03:37:26.730 --> 03:37:28.730
as you could probably
tell from his pose.

03:37:28.730 --> 03:37:31.010
He imitates Napoleon, in fact.

03:37:31.010 --> 03:37:35.150
But he has this long, luxurious
black beard that was described

03:37:35.150 --> 03:37:37.460
as very shiny and glistening.

03:37:37.460 --> 03:37:39.490
And he was quite a clothes horse.

03:37:39.490 --> 03:37:45.160
And you will -- I will refer
to that briefly later on.

03:37:47.770 --> 03:37:52.790
The very earliest rock relief
carving we know of are four reliefs

03:37:52.790 --> 03:37:55.510
in Western Iran carved
around the beginning

03:37:55.510 --> 03:38:00.390
of the second millennium B.C.E.
by the rulers of Lullubi,

03:38:00.390 --> 03:38:04.280
a mountainous kingdom in the
region, in which they proclaim

03:38:04.280 --> 03:38:07.390
and show the victories
over their enemies.

03:38:07.390 --> 03:38:13.410
You are just -- you're looking
at one of them, Anubanini,

03:38:13.410 --> 03:38:16.600
and you see him trampling
on the body

03:38:16.600 --> 03:38:19.700
of his most important
defeated enemy.

03:38:19.700 --> 03:38:23.900
And facing him is the goddess
Ishtar, whom he acknowledges

03:38:23.900 --> 03:38:25.920
as helping him, being on his side

03:38:25.920 --> 03:38:30.470
so he could have his --
achieve this victory.

03:38:33.410 --> 03:38:40.740
This monumental means of glorifying
royal power inspired 25 centuries

03:38:40.740 --> 03:38:44.690
later the Achaemenid
Darius the Great

03:38:44.690 --> 03:38:47.290
to commemorate his
military victories

03:38:47.290 --> 03:38:52.360
on a mountainside not
too far away at Bisitun.

03:38:52.360 --> 03:38:56.680
Succeeding Elamitian,
Parthian, and Sasanian monarchs,

03:38:56.680 --> 03:38:58.090
continued this tradition

03:38:58.090 --> 03:39:02.980
of immortalizing their
kingship and military triumphs.

03:39:02.980 --> 03:39:08.070
Rock relief sculpture reached its
apogee under the Sasanian kings,

03:39:08.070 --> 03:39:11.330
especially those of the
third and fourth centuries,

03:39:11.330 --> 03:39:18.540
in particular Ardashir I,
and you see him in the --

03:39:18.540 --> 03:39:22.130
at the top receiving his
investiture, his right to rule,

03:39:22.130 --> 03:39:30.330
from Ahura Mazda; Shapur
I, the second one, that --

03:39:30.330 --> 03:39:32.440
who also receives his investiture

03:39:32.440 --> 03:39:41.460
from the great god Ahura
Mazda; and Shapurs II and III.

03:39:41.460 --> 03:39:45.640
I also show you two reliefs
made for the last important king

03:39:45.640 --> 03:39:50.910
of the dynasty, Khosrow II, in
the larger grotto at Taq-e Bustan

03:39:50.910 --> 03:39:58.850 position:56%
in Kermanshah, the same province as
the reliefs of Anubanini and Darius.

03:39:58.850 --> 03:40:03.570
For the Sasanians, rock relief
was a major artistic medium

03:40:03.570 --> 03:40:08.280
in which they expressed imperial
ideas about divine investiture,

03:40:08.280 --> 03:40:13.780
legitimacy, royal succession,
and sheer military might.

03:40:13.780 --> 03:40:18.880
Rock reliefs attributable to the
Sasanian period total nearly 40,

03:40:18.880 --> 03:40:24.650
and 34 of them can be identified
with specific Sasanian kings.

03:40:24.650 --> 03:40:27.920
With the exception of one
relief in Afghanistan,

03:40:27.920 --> 03:40:35.890 position:56%
which Touraj showed you earlier in
the morning, all are in Iran proper.

03:40:35.890 --> 03:40:39.220
Most date to the third
and fourth centuries.

03:40:39.220 --> 03:40:44.890
Significantly, almost all of them
are located in Fars province,

03:40:44.890 --> 03:40:47.090
which was the geographical
foundation

03:40:47.090 --> 03:40:51.680
of not only the Sasanian dynasty,
but that of the Achaemenid.

03:40:51.680 --> 03:40:55.640
With the fall of the
Sasanians, monumental sculpture

03:40:55.640 --> 03:40:58.500
from living rock was
all but abandoned,

03:40:58.500 --> 03:41:02.490
although successive Islamic
dynasties such as the Buyid,

03:41:02.490 --> 03:41:07.230
the Mongols, and the Safavids
left many inscriptions carved

03:41:07.230 --> 03:41:13.690 position:56%
into living rock, none continued the
art of monumental relief sculpture.

03:41:13.690 --> 03:41:19.700 position:56%
To be sure, the major pictorial,
and especially the figurative themes

03:41:19.700 --> 03:41:24.350
of pre-Islamic Iran, specifically
those that had been employed

03:41:24.350 --> 03:41:29.890
by the Sasanians, "Razm o
Basim," Fighting and Feasting,

03:41:29.890 --> 03:41:35.870 position:56%
along with the hunt and enthronement
scenes continued to be depicted

03:41:35.870 --> 03:41:41.260
in painting, metalwork, ceramics,
and textiles as you see here

03:41:41.260 --> 03:41:45.780
in examples from Islamic times.

03:41:45.780 --> 03:41:49.880
But it was only in the
reign of Fath-Ali Shah Qajar

03:41:49.880 --> 03:41:53.660
that figurative monumental
rock carving was again made.

03:41:53.660 --> 03:41:58.410
In this talk, I'll survey
most of the Qajar reliefs,

03:41:58.410 --> 03:42:01.640
showing their debt to
those of the Sasanians.

03:42:01.640 --> 03:42:05.780
I'll suggest why Fath-Ali
Shah revived this ancient art,

03:42:05.780 --> 03:42:10.400
and end by contrasting the use of
Sasanian models in the first part

03:42:10.400 --> 03:42:16.310
of the 19th century with the
change in the scale, iconography,

03:42:16.310 --> 03:42:19.600
and even medium of relief
carving that prevailed

03:42:19.600 --> 03:42:22.090
in the second part of the century.

03:42:22.090 --> 03:42:26.870
And I shall briefly
suggest a reason why.

03:42:26.870 --> 03:42:32.360
Of the eight reliefs known
from the Qajar period,

03:42:32.360 --> 03:42:34.930
seven can be attributed
to Fath-Ali Shah

03:42:34.930 --> 03:42:37.090
or to one of his numerous progeny.

03:42:37.090 --> 03:42:40.600
The eighth was ordered
in the late 19th century

03:42:40.600 --> 03:42:46.110
by Fath-Ali Shah's great
grandson Nasr al-Din Shah.

03:42:47.210 --> 03:42:51.550
I'm showing you one of the
earlies of Fath-Ali Shah's relief,

03:42:51.550 --> 03:42:55.560
which is found in Northern
Iran in the mountainous region

03:42:55.560 --> 03:42:59.080
of Firuzkuh northeast of
Teheran, and I'm sure many

03:42:59.080 --> 03:43:04.650
in this room have hiked up
there, maybe in their youth,

03:43:04.650 --> 03:43:08.490
and perhaps have seen the relief.

03:43:08.490 --> 03:43:14.270
These mountains, which separate
Firuzkuh from the Mazandaran plain,

03:43:14.270 --> 03:43:17.450
were the main summer
quarters of the Qajar tribe,

03:43:17.450 --> 03:43:20.160
providing rich hunting
grounds for the court.

03:43:20.160 --> 03:43:23.530
And Fath-Ali Shah had
a hunting lodge there.

03:43:23.530 --> 03:43:27.850
It was also there in 1808 or 1817,

03:43:27.850 --> 03:43:32.490
depending upon how the
accompanying inscription is read,

03:43:32.490 --> 03:43:38.110
that he commemorated his
exploits in this relief.

03:43:38.110 --> 03:43:42.500
Filling the frame are not only
just the Shah and his prey --

03:43:42.500 --> 03:43:48.760
I'm sorry -- and his prey, but 18
of his many sons in attendance.

03:43:48.760 --> 03:43:51.050
I believe he had about 63 sons,

03:43:51.050 --> 03:43:54.260
and they never counted
all his daughters.

03:43:56.330 --> 03:44:00.430
The relief may commemorate
a particular hunt while also

03:44:00.430 --> 03:44:04.180
reproducing, on a grand scale,
paintings of hunting scenes

03:44:04.180 --> 03:44:07.370
that were popular with
the shah and his court.

03:44:07.370 --> 03:44:09.680
And you're looking at
an example of a painting

03:44:09.680 --> 03:44:14.210
on lacquer showing
Fath-Ali Shah hunting.

03:44:14.210 --> 03:44:21.190
His -- again, his black beard
just in the wind behind him.

03:44:21.190 --> 03:44:26.240
The subject matter harks back
to ancient Iranian images,

03:44:26.240 --> 03:44:28.060
in particular the density

03:44:28.060 --> 03:44:31.850
of the composition recalls
the monumental hunting reliefs

03:44:31.850 --> 03:44:38.080
in Khosrow II's iwan at
Taq-e Bustan, as well as,

03:44:38.080 --> 03:44:42.460
as you can see above, this
late Sasanian hunting plate

03:44:42.460 --> 03:44:46.560
on which the king pursues
a number of different game.

03:44:46.560 --> 03:44:55.830
It was at Taq-e Bustan
sometime between 1821 and 1828

03:44:55.830 --> 03:44:58.290
that a courtier had
carved this relief

03:44:58.290 --> 03:45:02.520
to memorialize Mohammad
Ali Mirza Dowlat-Shah,

03:45:02.520 --> 03:45:04.400
one of Fath-Ali Shah's sons,

03:45:04.400 --> 03:45:09.190
and Governor of Kermanshah
who had died in 1821.

03:45:09.190 --> 03:45:14.200
And so in the upper left you
see him attended by his sons

03:45:14.200 --> 03:45:19.190
and chief eunuch, ensconced on
a high-back throne, his posture

03:45:19.190 --> 03:45:22.720
and physiognomy very much
like that of his father

03:45:22.720 --> 03:45:29.210
who in numerous paintings sits
on a similar chair throne.

03:45:29.210 --> 03:45:34.000
The relief was placed above the
gray panel showing Khosrow II's

03:45:34.000 --> 03:45:35.530
boar hung.

03:45:35.530 --> 03:45:39.960
Its placement at the same height of
the figure of Khosrow on the rear

03:45:39.960 --> 03:45:44.670
of the grotto, on this rear wall,
has prompted Prudence Harper

03:45:44.670 --> 03:45:51.240
to observe that "The Sasanian King
of Kings is reduced to functioning

03:45:51.240 --> 03:45:55.770 position:56%
as Mohammad Ali Mirza's doorkeeper."

03:45:55.770 --> 03:45:58.510
It's a very nice conceit.

03:46:00.010 --> 03:46:04.460
Moving south to Shiraz, the
capital of Farz province,

03:46:04.460 --> 03:46:10.060
we find this imposing image
created between 1823 and 1825,

03:46:10.060 --> 03:46:12.370
when it was mentioned
by a British traveler

03:46:12.370 --> 03:46:15.750
as having recently been completed.

03:46:15.750 --> 03:46:21.270
Unfortunately, it is greatly
eroded over the years.

03:46:21.270 --> 03:46:30.840
It's unprotected, and when I
last saw it about 10 years ago,

03:46:30.840 --> 03:46:35.260
it had been -- people had
taken potshots at it --

03:46:35.260 --> 03:46:38.910
at the heads, as you can see.

03:46:38.910 --> 03:46:43.410
But I hope you can make out
the rigidly frontal figure

03:46:43.410 --> 03:46:49.100
of Fath-Ali Shah, flanked by two
standing also frontal figures.

03:46:49.100 --> 03:46:54.310 position:56%
Set high in the Tangeh Allahu Akbar,
the traditional entry into Shiraz

03:46:54.310 --> 03:46:59.380
from the north, the relief lacks
an identifying inscription,

03:46:59.380 --> 03:47:03.660
but the enthroned monarch
is clearly Fath-Ali Shah,

03:47:03.660 --> 03:47:07.030
recognized by his luxuriant beard,

03:47:07.030 --> 03:47:10.180
which had been originally
painted black, but in fact,

03:47:10.180 --> 03:47:14.410
I should say that all the reliefs
were painted, Qajar reliefs,

03:47:14.410 --> 03:47:20.610
as well as Sasanian reliefs,
as well as Achaemenid reliefs,

03:47:21.820 --> 03:47:28.080
and quite garishly I must say,
very shocking to our eyes.

03:47:28.080 --> 03:47:29.830
We're not used to this.

03:47:29.830 --> 03:47:33.720
Anyway, Fath-Ali Shah is
flanked by his heir apparent,

03:47:33.720 --> 03:47:38.340
Abbas Mirza to your
right, and to your left,

03:47:38.340 --> 03:47:43.190
Abbas Mirza's son Mohammad Mirza

03:47:43.190 --> 03:47:49.490
who in 1834 succeeded Fath-Ali
Shah as Mohammad Shah Qajar.

03:47:49.490 --> 03:47:52.150
Fath-Ali Shad kneels
on the Takht-e Marmar,

03:47:52.150 --> 03:47:54.670
the famous marble throne
upon which he

03:47:54.670 --> 03:47:57.830
and successive monarchs
were crowned.

03:47:57.830 --> 03:48:01.300
Framing the scene are the
twisted marble columns

03:48:01.300 --> 03:48:06.790 position:56%
that the first Qajar ruler,
Fath-Ali Shah's uncle Agha Mohammad,

03:48:06.790 --> 03:48:13.420
carted off to Teheran from Karim
Khan Zand's palace in Shiraz

03:48:13.420 --> 03:48:19.180
when he defeated the Zand dynasty
and gained the Persian throne.

03:48:19.180 --> 03:48:23.870
These furnishing indicate that
the scent takes place in Teheran.

03:48:23.870 --> 03:48:27.560 position:56%
And as I've previously written about
the relief, I believe it was carved

03:48:27.560 --> 03:48:30.590
on the orders of Fath-Ali Shah
to demonstrate to the people

03:48:30.590 --> 03:48:34.490
of Farz the correct
succession to the throne.

03:48:34.490 --> 03:48:39.390
It became necessary to do this in
1822 after the Shah heard rumors

03:48:39.390 --> 03:48:45.290
that two of his other sons, Hassan
Ali Mirza, Governor of Khorasan,

03:48:45.290 --> 03:48:48.170 position:56%
and Hossein Ali Mirza, Farman Farma,

03:48:48.170 --> 03:48:51.960
Governor of Shiraz,
were planning a revolt.

03:48:51.960 --> 03:48:55.090
Hassan Ali Mirza resigned
his governorship,

03:48:55.090 --> 03:49:00.540
but Hossein Ali Mirza did not
and continued to rule in Shiraz.

03:49:00.540 --> 03:49:06.310 position:56%
The frontal hieratic pose of the
Shah, flanked by his intended heirs,

03:49:06.310 --> 03:49:13.490
recalls the enthronement relief
of the Sasanian ruler Bahram II

03:49:13.490 --> 03:49:17.710
at Sarab Bahram, which
is not far from Saharz

03:49:17.710 --> 03:49:21.590
and surely must have
served as an inspiration.

03:49:24.130 --> 03:49:30.100
I show you two more reliefs
dated to the early 1830s,

03:49:30.100 --> 03:49:33.110 position:56%
Fath-Ali Shah's last decade of rule.

03:49:33.110 --> 03:49:36.070
Both were carved at
Rayy, south of Teheran.

03:49:36.070 --> 03:49:41.350
And this one on a boulder
at Kuh-e Sorsorreh shows him

03:49:41.350 --> 03:49:46.370
with long beard flying as he spears
a lion, a more active portrayal

03:49:46.370 --> 03:49:49.630
than the usual static enthronement.

03:49:49.630 --> 03:49:53.850
It's possible that this daring-do
was inspired by the Sasanian relief

03:49:53.850 --> 03:49:56.940
that had originally been
carved on the boulder,

03:49:56.940 --> 03:50:00.230
which probably depicted Shapur I.

03:50:00.230 --> 03:50:02.960
And you see it here
in this drawing made

03:50:02.960 --> 03:50:05.380
by Cerulean Usli [assumed
spelling] during his stay

03:50:05.380 --> 03:50:08.760
in Persia from 1811 to 1812.

03:50:08.760 --> 03:50:12.400
It's likely that the
Qajar shah's appropriation

03:50:12.400 --> 03:50:19.670
of this ancient relief added to the
power and prestige of his image.

03:50:19.670 --> 03:50:24.620
Fath-Ali Shah's last relief
at Rayy is this enthronement

03:50:24.620 --> 03:50:29.970
at Cheshmeh Ali, carved three
years before his death in 1834.

03:50:29.970 --> 03:50:35.970
And again, for nostalgia's
sake, in the upper left some

03:50:35.970 --> 03:50:39.740
of you might remember it was
a fine place to picnicking,

03:50:39.740 --> 03:50:44.010
and people washed their
carpets at the spring.

03:50:44.010 --> 03:50:46.530
It's a very old slide.

03:50:48.070 --> 03:50:55.070 position:56%
The relief reprises the central
portion of a much earlier well-known

03:50:55.070 --> 03:50:58.400
and much-copied life-sized
wall painting made

03:50:58.400 --> 03:51:01.570
by Abdullah Khan 20 years earlier

03:51:01.570 --> 03:51:05.940
for the Negaristan
palace outside of Teheran.

03:51:05.940 --> 03:51:10.170 position:56%
Its subject is an imaginary New
Year reception at the Persian court.

03:51:10.170 --> 03:51:15.520
The enthroned shah is flanked by
his sons and retainers as well

03:51:15.520 --> 03:51:17.650
as by all the foreign envoys

03:51:17.650 --> 03:51:21.860
and ambassadors he had
received on different occasions.

03:51:21.860 --> 03:51:28.360
Its composition echoes the great
reliefs of Shapur and that of --

03:51:28.360 --> 03:51:33.100
I don't think it moved -- sorry.

03:51:36.810 --> 03:51:40.790
Yes, sorry, I have left
out a slide, but it's okay.

03:51:40.790 --> 03:51:49.820 position:56%
Anyway, it echoes the great reliefs
of Shapur I and the one of Shapur II

03:51:49.820 --> 03:51:57.380 position:56%
at Bishapur, which display images
of and submission of subject peoples

03:51:57.380 --> 03:52:01.480
from all parts of the
Sasanian empire.

03:52:01.480 --> 03:52:06.620
In the Negaristan painting and
at Cheshmeh Ali, representatives

03:52:06.620 --> 03:52:09.640
of Britain, France, India, Arabia,

03:52:09.640 --> 03:52:14.030
and the Ottoman Empire pay their
respects to the Qajar Shah.

03:52:14.030 --> 03:52:19.450
But this is purely symbolic, as
they never all actually converged

03:52:19.450 --> 03:52:23.370 position:56%
on the Qajar court at a single time.

03:52:23.370 --> 03:52:28.270
If the image of foreigners
coming to pay respect

03:52:28.270 --> 03:52:34.230
to the Persian shah reminds you of
the Great Procession at Persepolis

03:52:34.230 --> 03:52:39.430 position:56%
to which -- in which all the subject
nations bring gifts or tribute

03:52:39.430 --> 03:52:45.450
to the American King of Kings,
I'd give you an A for effort,

03:52:45.450 --> 03:52:48.430
but otherwise you would be wrong.

03:52:48.430 --> 03:52:53.770
And that's because the
enthroned figure of Darius

03:52:53.770 --> 03:52:57.670
and his Crown Prince Xerxes
had occupied the center

03:52:57.670 --> 03:53:01.220
of the composition on the
northern and eastern staircases

03:53:01.220 --> 03:53:05.520
of the Apadana, but the
Qajars never saw them,

03:53:05.520 --> 03:53:10.540
as those panels had been
replaced by Darius' son Xerxes

03:53:10.540 --> 03:53:14.120
with an inscriptional
panel flanked by guards.

03:53:14.120 --> 03:53:17.590 position:56%
And you see that in the lower slide.

03:53:17.590 --> 03:53:19.810
And this, of course,
is what we see today.

03:53:19.810 --> 03:53:24.520
The -- in the center is the
drawing of one of the two panels.

03:53:24.520 --> 03:53:31.780 position:56%
And you will see them because they
were found during proper excavations

03:53:31.780 --> 03:53:33.840
of Persepolis in the
treasury building.

03:53:33.840 --> 03:53:37.440
So they had been removed by
the heir who really didn't want

03:53:37.440 --> 03:53:42.440
to show himself as being
subservient to his father.

03:53:42.440 --> 03:53:48.090
At least that is what
we have accepted.

03:53:48.090 --> 03:53:51.750
So this is what we see today.

03:53:51.750 --> 03:53:55.540
However, the grandeur
of the entire procession

03:53:55.540 --> 03:54:01.990
on the eastern stairway became
visible only in the 1930s

03:54:01.990 --> 03:54:06.400
with the scientific
excavation of Persepolis.

03:54:06.400 --> 03:54:09.890
And this is really what
the Qajars would have seen,

03:54:09.890 --> 03:54:16.710 position:56%
and even into the early 20th century
this is what Persepolis looked like.

03:54:16.710 --> 03:54:21.850
And what was exposed, which was the
northern staircase of the Apadana,

03:54:21.850 --> 03:54:27.400
was in a ruinous state
and had also been looted.

03:54:27.400 --> 03:54:33.190
Many reliefs that now
grace some of our museums

03:54:33.190 --> 03:54:36.810
around the world came from there.

03:54:36.810 --> 03:54:40.430
In short, Fath-Ali Shah and
his artists were not inspired

03:54:40.430 --> 03:54:42.720
by these Achaemenid reliefs.

03:54:42.720 --> 03:54:45.510
Rather, the image of the
enthroned ruler flanked

03:54:45.510 --> 03:54:49.020
by courtiers was a topos
of Persian painting.

03:54:49.020 --> 03:54:53.260
And as you've seen, one that
harks back to Sasanian rule.

03:54:53.260 --> 03:54:56.620
Before Fath-Ali Shah
assumed the Qajar throne,

03:54:56.620 --> 03:54:59.890
he had served Agha
Mohammad Shah as Governor

03:54:59.890 --> 03:55:03.680
of Farz province with
his seat in Shiraz.

03:55:03.680 --> 03:55:07.040
As you saw on the map at
the beginning of my talk,

03:55:07.040 --> 03:55:11.680
Farz is home to a trove
of Sasanian reliefs.

03:55:11.680 --> 03:55:16.820
Of the surviving 40, 28
are in Farz province,

03:55:16.820 --> 03:55:19.810
and most are not far from Shiraz.

03:55:19.810 --> 03:55:24.910
Truly their imposing scale and
courtly imagery of enthronement

03:55:24.910 --> 03:55:32.490 position:56%
and jousting inspired the young Baba
Khan, as Fath-Ali Shah was known,

03:55:32.490 --> 03:55:40.100
while his uncle Agha
Mohammad ruled in Persia.

03:55:40.100 --> 03:55:41.900
As I hope I've demonstrated,

03:55:41.900 --> 03:55:45.670
rock relief carving flourished
during Fath-Ali Shah's reign,

03:55:45.670 --> 03:55:47.650
and only with his reign.

03:55:47.650 --> 03:55:51.790
With his death in 1834, this
art form came to an end,

03:55:51.790 --> 03:55:55.930
except for a one-time revival
under Nasr al-Din Shah,

03:55:55.930 --> 03:55:58.570 position:56%
which is what you're looking at now.

03:55:58.570 --> 03:56:04.660
Bearing the date of 1878 is this
monumental relief commemorating the

03:56:04.660 --> 03:56:08.910 position:56%
reconstruction of a road through the
Haraz River Valley in Mazandaran.

03:56:08.910 --> 03:56:11.660
That's in the north.

03:56:11.660 --> 03:56:16.670
In the center you see the Shah on
horseback flanked by courtiers,

03:56:16.670 --> 03:56:20.760
one of which is his Minister
for Public Works, and another,

03:56:20.760 --> 03:56:24.900
the second from the right -- I'm
sorry, I don't have a pointer --

03:56:24.900 --> 03:56:27.950
is his favorite court photographer,

03:56:27.950 --> 03:56:32.090
Aga Riza Aqa Spash-e
[assumed spelling].

03:56:32.090 --> 03:56:36.610
Please notice the extreme fidelity
in the rendering of the Shah,

03:56:36.610 --> 03:56:39.390
his courtiers, and his horse.

03:56:39.390 --> 03:56:43.190
This is due to a great
familiarity with photography,

03:56:43.190 --> 03:56:48.410
for Nasr al-Din Shah was himself an
avid and accomplished photographer

03:56:48.410 --> 03:56:52.420
and advanced the use of
this art throughout Persia.

03:56:52.420 --> 03:56:56.710
Also notable in this relief is how
the figures are organized in space

03:56:56.710 --> 03:57:00.550
and the use of different
heights of relief to crate depth.

03:57:00.550 --> 03:57:05.210 position:56%
This helps to suggest a kind of
perspective that is alien to ancient

03:57:05.210 --> 03:57:08.680
and traditional Persian
art, but is characteristic

03:57:08.680 --> 03:57:11.500
of this late Qajar period.

03:57:11.500 --> 03:57:15.550
An increased interest in
and resulting influence

03:57:15.550 --> 03:57:19.730
of the West impacted
strongly on Qajar art,

03:57:19.730 --> 03:57:23.870
as did the so-called
realism of photography.

03:57:23.870 --> 03:57:27.080
Thus, in the relief
we see a new take

03:57:27.080 --> 03:57:32.220
on the hierarchic courtly
mode of the ruler enthroned.

03:57:32.220 --> 03:57:40.160
And it's interesting to contrast
the two, the Sasanian Bahran II one

03:57:40.160 --> 03:57:44.840
and Fath-Ali Shah's
enthronement scene in Shiraz.

03:57:44.840 --> 03:57:51.430 position:56%
Interestingly, in this time of the
Haraz Road relief and Qajar interest

03:57:51.430 --> 03:57:55.680 position:56%
in photography, a different kind of
relief sculpture was being developed

03:57:55.680 --> 03:57:58.800
in Iran, specifically
in Farz province.

03:57:58.800 --> 03:58:07.390
Beginning in the 1860s, a number of
grand houses in Shiraz were built

03:58:07.390 --> 03:58:10.930
and embellished with stone
relief sculptures as well

03:58:10.930 --> 03:58:14.310
as plaster carvings
and ceramic tiles

03:58:14.310 --> 03:58:16.740
that copy Achaemenid sculpture,

03:58:16.740 --> 03:58:20.070
specifically the reliefs
from Persepolis.

03:58:20.070 --> 03:58:24.920
There's time to show you
examples from one of --

03:58:24.920 --> 03:58:27.540
only one of these houses.

03:58:27.540 --> 03:58:33.350
It is the Narengestan, built
sometime between 1879 and 1885.

03:58:33.350 --> 03:58:40.550
And no doubt some of you here have
visited it either because you lived

03:58:40.550 --> 03:58:46.250
in Shiraz or you visited Shiraz,
and maybe you grew up in Shiraz.

03:58:46.250 --> 03:58:49.570
I know that one person
in the audience here has.

03:58:49.570 --> 03:58:54.200
What prompted this
interest in Achaemenid,

03:58:54.200 --> 03:58:57.520
specifically Persepolitan imagery?

03:58:57.520 --> 03:59:02.620
Centuries of Persian Islamic art
had reverberated with faint echoes

03:59:02.620 --> 03:59:06.200
of the art developed
under Cyrus and Darius.

03:59:06.200 --> 03:59:09.180
And these reverberations had
been channeled through the filter

03:59:09.180 --> 03:59:12.440
of Sasanian artistic convention.

03:59:12.440 --> 03:59:14.990
I've already treated this
issue in several articles

03:59:14.990 --> 03:59:17.420
that focus on its various aspects.

03:59:17.420 --> 03:59:20.920
In the time remaining, suffice
it to say that knowledge

03:59:20.920 --> 03:59:25.080
of Persia's pre-Islamic
past had virtually been lost

03:59:25.080 --> 03:59:27.900
to the Persians themselves.

03:59:27.900 --> 03:59:31.380
The epic national history,
the "Shahnameh,"

03:59:31.380 --> 03:59:34.470
treats only the major
Sasanian rulers,

03:59:34.470 --> 03:59:40.010
the events of their reign only
vaguely remembered or romanticized.

03:59:40.010 --> 03:59:43.890
The Achaemenid dynasty
was even more obscure.

03:59:43.890 --> 03:59:47.850
In fact, it was virtually unknown.

03:59:47.850 --> 03:59:54.110
The "Shahnameh" mentions only the
last Achaeminic king, Darius III,

03:59:54.110 --> 03:59:59.390
but only as a foil for the
conquering and heroic Iskandar,

03:59:59.390 --> 04:00:03.280
Alexander the Great, who
is the legitimate ruler.

04:00:03.280 --> 04:00:09.950
But an important event occurred
in 1846 with the publication

04:00:09.950 --> 04:00:15.810 position:56%
by the military officer linguist and
diplomat, Henry Creswicke Rawlinson,

04:00:15.810 --> 04:00:17.960
of his reading of the
Old Persian text

04:00:17.960 --> 04:00:21.130
of Darius' inscription at Behistun.

04:00:21.130 --> 04:00:25.080
This introduced to mid-19th
century Persians the voice

04:00:25.080 --> 04:00:30.420
of a great Persian ruler of
an actual and far more ancient

04:00:30.420 --> 04:00:34.570
and powerful Persia than
hitherto they had known.

04:00:34.570 --> 04:00:39.750 position:56%
Through Darius' own words which
were translated into modern Persian,

04:00:39.750 --> 04:00:46.440 position:56%
almost immediately, Persians learned
about the first great Persian Empire

04:00:46.440 --> 04:00:50.220
that for its time,
rivaled that of any

04:00:50.220 --> 04:00:54.400
of the European powers
past or current.

04:00:54.400 --> 04:00:57.850
At a time when Persia had to
stave off Russian, British,

04:00:57.850 --> 04:01:00.360
and French attempts
to bring the country

04:01:00.360 --> 04:01:03.720
into their respective
spheres of influence,

04:01:03.720 --> 04:01:07.610
this knowledge became a source
of national pride and fed

04:01:07.610 --> 04:01:09.500
into the growing interest
on the part

04:01:09.500 --> 04:01:13.770
of many Persian intellectuals
in nation building.

04:01:13.770 --> 04:01:18.230
Thus interest turned to such
Achaemenid sites as Pasargadae

04:01:18.230 --> 04:01:22.260
and to the tombs of the
Achaemenid kings at Naqsh-e Rustam

04:01:22.260 --> 04:01:28.210 position:56%
but most particular to Persepolis
or Parsa, hitherto known to Persians

04:01:28.210 --> 04:01:32.370
from early Islamic times as
Sad Stun, "Hundred Columns" --

04:01:32.370 --> 04:01:37.210
chihil minara "Forty Minarets" --
or as it is still called today,

04:01:37.210 --> 04:01:40.790
Takht-e Jamshid for
Throne of Jamshid.

04:01:40.790 --> 04:01:44.130
[Inaudible] must have been aware
of Persepolis but we have --

04:01:44.130 --> 04:01:46.140
he would have considered
it the creation

04:01:46.140 --> 04:01:49.150
of mythological or
supernatural beings.

04:01:49.150 --> 04:01:50.820
Its carvings unfamiliar

04:01:50.820 --> 04:01:54.470
and unidentifiable
and hence meaningless.

04:01:54.470 --> 04:01:58.740
In contrast, he would have
recognized in the reliefs

04:01:58.740 --> 04:02:02.340
of the [Inaudible] the traditional
privileges and duties of kingship,

04:02:02.340 --> 04:02:06.290
enthronement, homage,
fighting and the hunt,

04:02:06.290 --> 04:02:09.510
all produced on a monumental scale,

04:02:09.510 --> 04:02:12.640
worthy models for this
[inaudible] monarch.

04:02:12.640 --> 04:02:14.440
Thank you.

04:02:14.440 --> 04:02:23.040
[ Applause ]

04:02:23.040 --> 04:02:24.870
&gt;&gt; Hirad Dinavari:
Thank you very much.

04:02:24.870 --> 04:02:27.340
And we do have someone
from Shiraz here,

04:02:27.340 --> 04:02:30.500
Dr. Fatemeh Keshavarz
is from Shiraz.

04:02:30.500 --> 04:02:33.230
So one of our speakers, exactly.

04:02:33.230 --> 04:02:36.430
Last but not least from
University of Maryland,

04:02:36.430 --> 04:02:42.060
I would like to introduce
Dr. Ida Meftahi.

04:02:42.060 --> 04:02:47.750
She currently holds a Visiting
Assistantship Professorship

04:02:47.750 --> 04:02:52.180
in Contemporary Iranian Culture
and Society at the Roshan Institute

04:02:52.180 --> 04:02:55.440
for Persian Studies,
University of Maryland.

04:02:55.440 --> 04:02:59.200
She completed her doctoral
studies at the University

04:02:59.200 --> 04:03:04.080
of Toronto's Department of Near
and Middle Eastern Civilizations

04:03:04.080 --> 04:03:09.730
and was the postdoctoral fellow
at the Institute for the Arts

04:03:09.730 --> 04:03:13.480
and Humanities at Pennsylvania
State University.

04:03:13.480 --> 04:03:17.980
Her first book, <i>Gender
and Dance in Modern Iran,</i>

04:03:17.980 --> 04:03:23.840
<i>Biopolitics on Stage</i>
was released in May 2016.

04:03:23.840 --> 04:03:26.840
In addition to teaching
interdisciplinary courses

04:03:26.840 --> 04:03:31.900
on Modern Iran, she is the director
of Lalehzar Digital Project,

04:03:31.900 --> 04:03:36.830
a component of the Roshan
Initiative for Digital Humanities,

04:03:36.830 --> 04:03:42.270
as well as faculty
adviser for Roshangar,

04:03:42.270 --> 04:03:46.320
Roshan Undergraduate
Journal for Persian Studies.

04:03:46.320 --> 04:03:47.620
Thank you, Ida.

04:03:47.620 --> 04:03:49.220
It's great to have you here again.

04:03:49.220 --> 04:03:53.270
She gave us a wonderful talk on her
book and now we have her talking

04:03:53.270 --> 04:03:58.340
about dance and Sasanian bringing
the Sasanian Realm to the present

04:03:58.340 --> 04:04:00.700
by taking it out of antiquity and
bringing it to the contemporary.

04:04:00.700 --> 04:04:02.500
Thank you.

04:04:02.500 --> 04:04:07.170
[ Applause ]

04:04:07.170 --> 04:04:08.470
&gt;&gt; Ida Meftahi: Thank you.

04:04:08.470 --> 04:04:09.770
Greetings, everyone.

04:04:09.770 --> 04:04:14.390
In November 1921 on the
stage of the Grand Hotel

04:04:14.390 --> 04:04:18.690
on Tehran's Lalehzar Street,
the historical musical Parichihr

04:04:18.690 --> 04:04:22.290
and Parizad was staged
twice for the benefit

04:04:22.290 --> 04:04:29.210 position:56%
of the newspaper [Inaudible] --
newspapers [Inaudible] respectively.

04:04:29.210 --> 04:04:35.450
Advertised as a play that would
"inform the audience of the customs

04:04:35.450 --> 04:04:41.430
of Sasanian era" and written by
a young playwright Reza Kamal,

04:04:41.430 --> 04:04:44.350
who later took up the
pen name "Shahrzad".

04:04:44.350 --> 04:04:48.810
The show drew several hundreds of
enthusiastic audiences comprised

04:04:48.810 --> 04:04:51.960
of both ticket payers
and trespassers.

04:04:51.960 --> 04:04:56.580
The significance of the play
is reflected in the debased --

04:04:56.580 --> 04:05:00.880
debates it instigated in the
periodicals in the following weeks

04:05:00.880 --> 04:05:04.820 position:56%
about various aspects of performance
including the actors' depiction

04:05:04.820 --> 04:05:09.610
of characters and the venue, all
of which provide us with insights

04:05:09.610 --> 04:05:14.070
into politics, perception,
and expectations pertaining

04:05:14.070 --> 04:05:18.910
to staging ancient Iranian
history in early 20th century.

04:05:18.910 --> 04:05:23.610
An audience member, in defense of
the play wrote the following letter

04:05:23.610 --> 04:05:28.990
to the playwright, "Mr. Reza
Kamal, I came to the show knowing

04:05:28.990 --> 04:05:31.960
that you brought a forgotten
part of Iranian history

04:05:31.960 --> 04:05:36.210
to life using historical
evidence -- evidences.

04:05:36.210 --> 04:05:39.480
I was especially excited
that the play is

04:05:39.480 --> 04:05:42.500
about King Anurshirvan's
famous dream,

04:05:42.500 --> 04:05:44.810
the one that many historians
have described.

04:05:44.810 --> 04:05:48.140
I couldn't believe that a
young Iranian would be able

04:05:48.140 --> 04:05:51.990
to convert this country -- his
country's history into a play.

04:05:51.990 --> 04:05:56.740
You have selected to depict
the era of the just king

04:05:56.740 --> 04:05:59.290
that all Iranians are proud of

04:05:59.290 --> 04:06:02.860
and a beautiful episode
unique to this era."

04:06:02.860 --> 04:06:09.040
Thus far, the letter tells us that
firstly, the notion of history

04:06:09.040 --> 04:06:12.030
in this context was
intertwined with nationalism

04:06:12.030 --> 04:06:13.990
and glory of ancient Iran.

04:06:13.990 --> 04:06:19.480
And secondly, literary imagination
counted as historical evidence

04:06:19.480 --> 04:06:22.760
as the most recognized to
Anurshirvan's dream as far

04:06:22.760 --> 04:06:24.990
as those historic,
[inaudible] book of the kings.

04:06:24.990 --> 04:06:31.130
The letter then continued, "But
then the day after the show,

04:06:31.130 --> 04:06:32.730
I was surprised to see

04:06:32.730 --> 04:06:36.430
that [Inaudible] itself had
published a negative review

04:06:36.430 --> 04:06:37.730
about your play.

04:06:37.730 --> 04:06:42.350
I'm writing to asking not to get
discouraged by these criticisms.

04:06:42.350 --> 04:06:45.240
They have complained that
depicting Parichihr whose dead body

04:06:45.240 --> 04:06:51.730 position:56%
on stage was not appropriate for the
20th century and that it was a sign

04:06:51.730 --> 04:06:53.030
of savagery, [inaudible].

04:06:53.030 --> 04:06:55.580
You shouldn't take these
interpretations seriously

04:06:55.580 --> 04:06:58.270
as such scenes are
prevalent and important phase

04:06:58.270 --> 04:07:03.190
around the world including
Salome and Othello.

04:07:03.190 --> 04:07:05.860
If you -- if having a dead body

04:07:05.860 --> 04:07:08.810
on stage is savagery
then all these writers

04:07:08.810 --> 04:07:14.480
of the civilized world
must have been savages.

04:07:14.480 --> 04:07:18.180
You were also condemned for
having a fortune teller who speaks

04:07:18.180 --> 04:07:21.190
from the other world but of
course, you're showing an era

04:07:21.190 --> 04:07:25.340
in which this idea was
very indeed widespread."

04:07:25.340 --> 04:07:29.000
This part of the letter tells us --

04:07:29.000 --> 04:07:34.060 position:56%
attest to the fact that when ancient
Iranian history was materialized

04:07:34.060 --> 04:07:38.550
on stage, it had to reflect the
values and rules of modern stage

04:07:38.550 --> 04:07:43.790
of 1920s and not of the Sasanian
era in which the plot was based.

04:07:43.790 --> 04:07:48.620
At the time, theatrical stage was
considered the site for display

04:07:48.620 --> 04:07:51.240
of modernity and a
school of morality

04:07:51.240 --> 04:07:53.540
and edification for its audience.

04:07:53.540 --> 04:07:56.220
Thus the backward signs of savagery

04:07:56.220 --> 04:08:01.060
and superstitious countered the
then modern Iranian notions.

04:08:01.060 --> 04:08:04.910
The letter then continued,
"A playwright has

04:08:04.910 --> 04:08:09.290
to depict the characters'
personalities and behaviors

04:08:09.290 --> 04:08:11.990
as much as their costumes.

04:08:11.990 --> 04:08:18.480
It would been ridiculous if you had
shown the [inaudible] dancing just

04:08:18.480 --> 04:08:22.280
as a young Belgian king
may dance with women

04:08:22.280 --> 04:08:24.340
or if you would have
depicted the courtiers

04:08:24.340 --> 04:08:27.700
of the 1st century
[inaudible] with ties or bowties

04:08:27.700 --> 04:08:30.910
of latest Parisian
fashion because some actors

04:08:30.910 --> 04:08:33.690
of Comedie Francaise may show
up [inaudible] on the stage."

04:08:33.690 --> 04:08:40.290
As evidence, no matter how much the
theatrical media of the time drew

04:08:40.290 --> 04:08:45.820
up on European inspirations or
dialogued with European aesthetics,

04:08:45.820 --> 04:08:50.440
vernacular and gender perceptions,
they are expected to be reflected

04:08:50.440 --> 04:08:55.570
in the depiction of important
historical characters especially

04:08:55.570 --> 04:08:56.870
the kings.

04:08:56.870 --> 04:08:59.440
In this case, dancing was
not considered appropriate

04:08:59.440 --> 04:09:02.050
for a [inaudible] Iranian king.

04:09:02.050 --> 04:09:07.910
However, as other sources on this
play indicate, it was acceptable

04:09:07.910 --> 04:09:13.770
for the female protagonist
Parichihr to dance and sing.

04:09:13.770 --> 04:09:16.170
Indeed, one of the most
important novelties

04:09:16.170 --> 04:09:20.010
of this play was the employment
of the young Armenian dancer

04:09:20.010 --> 04:09:23.800
and singer, [Inaudible]
Aqabayov to enact the role

04:09:23.800 --> 04:09:26.770
of Parichihr upon her
arrival from Europe

04:09:26.770 --> 04:09:30.720
where she received her
opera and ballet training.

04:09:30.720 --> 04:09:33.420
Praised widely for her sole --

04:09:33.420 --> 04:09:38.170
for her role as Parichihr which
literally means, fairy face,

04:09:38.170 --> 04:09:43.390
Aqabayov adopted the stage name
of Pari and became the star

04:09:43.390 --> 04:09:46.790
of Iranian stage for a decade.

04:09:46.790 --> 04:09:50.030
While there are no existing
images of her performance,

04:09:50.030 --> 04:09:54.170
a farfetched interpretation
on my behalf,

04:09:54.170 --> 04:10:02.060 position:56%
is to relate this balletic depiction
of the goddess Nahid on pointe shoes

04:10:02.060 --> 04:10:06.160
in the logo of the
periodical Nahid in 1920s

04:10:06.160 --> 04:10:08.860
to Madame Pari's success
at the time.

04:10:10.410 --> 04:10:16.830
Not only was Aqabayov's artistic
skillsets a novelty for that era

04:10:16.830 --> 04:10:21.740
but the public appearance
of female performers even

04:10:21.740 --> 04:10:27.150
on that modern stage was rare and
mostly limited to non-Muslims.

04:10:27.150 --> 04:10:30.810
In this era, most female
roles continued

04:10:30.810 --> 04:10:34.260
to be performed by
cross-dressed men.

04:10:34.260 --> 04:10:38.060
This was the case -- oops --

04:10:39.130 --> 04:10:43.940
with another important historical
opera contemporaneous to Parichihr

04:10:43.940 --> 04:10:49.730 position:56%
and Parizad which had been on the
stage of Grand Hotel since May 1921.

04:10:49.730 --> 04:10:53.350
This was the Resurrection of
Persian Kings in the Ruins

04:10:53.350 --> 04:10:59.690
of Mada'in written by the poet
and journalist Mirzah'i Eshghi.

04:10:59.690 --> 04:11:04.820
Writing the first historical opera
of its kind, Eshghi was inspired

04:11:04.820 --> 04:11:08.580
by his travel from Baghdad to Mosul

04:11:08.580 --> 04:11:13.090
where he encountered
the still glorious ruins

04:11:13.090 --> 04:11:15.910
of Sasanian [Inaudible].

04:11:15.910 --> 04:11:20.110
The script revolves around the
poet's own dream which unfolds

04:11:20.110 --> 04:11:24.700
against the backdrop of
this historical monument.

04:11:24.700 --> 04:11:31.480 position:56%
There he witnesses some of the major
ancient Iranian kings including

04:11:31.480 --> 04:11:36.720 position:56%
Cyrus, Darius, and [Inaudible] along
with Zoroaster, all of whom mourned

04:11:36.720 --> 04:11:42.130
for the condition of Iran in
1920 which was depicted as part

04:11:42.130 --> 04:11:47.340 position:56%
of the continuum of a dark age
which began with the "Arab Invasion"

04:11:47.340 --> 04:11:51.230
that had put an end to the
Golden Age of Sasanian Era.

04:11:51.230 --> 04:11:54.210
A significant role belonged to --

04:11:54.210 --> 04:11:57.680
in this play, belonged to
a Sasanian princess enacted

04:11:57.680 --> 04:12:01.630
by a cross-dressed man who
mourned for the poor condition

04:12:01.630 --> 04:12:07.950
of Iranian women symbolizing
modern Iran or all women of Iran

04:12:07.950 --> 04:12:12.310
and ancient Iranian princess
became a prevalent character type

04:12:12.310 --> 04:12:14.960
in nationalist plays and
operettas of that era.

04:12:14.960 --> 04:12:18.450
Similar to Parichihr and Parizad,

04:12:18.450 --> 04:12:23.020
Resurrection of Persian
Kings instigated responses

04:12:23.020 --> 04:12:27.340
for the audiences who recommended
a more appropriate attire

04:12:27.340 --> 04:12:29.090
for certain kings on stage.

04:12:29.090 --> 04:12:34.010
A favorable comment from
audience member reads,

04:12:34.010 --> 04:12:40.000
"This play is the best medium
for moving the sensitive hearts

04:12:40.000 --> 04:12:45.100 position:56%
who view Iranian kings [inaudible]
up in the ruins of Ctesiphon to pray

04:12:45.100 --> 04:12:46.940
for the progress of Iran.

04:12:46.940 --> 04:12:51.180
Accompanying them is Zoroaster
who begs for the bliss of Iran.

04:12:51.180 --> 04:12:56.360
How can not -- how can one
not be moved by these things?"

04:12:56.360 --> 04:13:08.230
While later stagings of
the Resurrection in 1923,

04:13:08.230 --> 04:13:13.830
Madame Pari took over the
role of the Sasanian princess.

04:13:13.830 --> 04:13:18.060
Raztakhiz's reference to Sasanian
history were indeed far more direct

04:13:18.060 --> 04:13:20.440
than Shahrzad's Parichihr
and Parizad

04:13:20.440 --> 04:13:24.260
and perhaps its success
prompted the selling

04:13:24.260 --> 04:13:28.160
of Shahrzad's play as
a Sasanian history.

04:13:28.160 --> 04:13:31.930
Visualizing the glorious
ancient Iranian history combined

04:13:31.930 --> 04:13:36.080
with nationalism and nostalgia as
well as binary characterization

04:13:36.080 --> 04:13:40.880
of us Iranians versus
them, the Arab invaders,

04:13:40.880 --> 04:13:44.160
was a recurring theme
even before these operas

04:13:44.160 --> 04:13:47.520
and it's continued afterwards.

04:13:47.520 --> 04:13:54.980
A good later example is
[Inaudible] written in 1927.

04:13:54.980 --> 04:13:57.820
Some of these plays
combine the ancient history

04:13:57.820 --> 04:14:01.060
with classical literature
including those dealing

04:14:01.060 --> 04:14:04.440
with [inaudible] namely [Inaudible]
which drew on ancient history

04:14:04.440 --> 04:14:14.580
to assign historical personas
to literary characters.

04:14:14.580 --> 04:14:21.080 position:56%
While others were based on
collaborations of historians, again,

04:14:21.080 --> 04:14:26.850
history in its early 20th
century sense with writers.

04:14:26.850 --> 04:14:30.240
These collaborations which
gradually became more conscious

04:14:30.240 --> 04:14:33.270
of archeological expeditions
and works

04:14:33.270 --> 04:14:35.750
of European Orientalist
scholars would lead

04:14:35.750 --> 04:14:41.520
to a more historically informed
detailing in the staging of plays.

04:14:41.520 --> 04:14:47.760
While Reza Shah's state is
nationalism promoted similar lines

04:14:47.760 --> 04:14:52.020
of thinking, it's important
to note that these authors

04:14:52.020 --> 04:14:54.730
that they're not necessarily
pro-state.

04:14:54.730 --> 04:15:05.860
In fact, Mirzah'i Eshghi was
murdered by the Pahlavi regime

04:15:05.860 --> 04:15:09.460
and Shahrzad committed suicide.

04:15:09.460 --> 04:15:15.020
An example of a pro-state
play is Zoroaster's Promise,

04:15:15.020 --> 04:15:20.130
[Inaudible] written in
1930 by [Inaudible].

04:15:20.130 --> 04:15:25.170
In this play, in the manner
of Eshghi's Resurrection

04:15:25.170 --> 04:15:35.320
of Iranian Kings, modern
Iran, Zoroaster, Darius I,

04:15:35.320 --> 04:15:38.500
[Inaudible] all visit the
playwright in his dream.

04:15:38.500 --> 04:15:40.480
The play culminates with all

04:15:40.480 --> 04:15:44.570
of these important figures praising
Reza Shah for his achievements.

04:15:44.570 --> 04:15:50.450 position:56%
In the words of the theater scholar,
[Inaudible], the goal of this genre

04:15:50.450 --> 04:15:54.460
of historical drama in that era
was to evoke emotional response

04:15:54.460 --> 04:15:59.720
in the audience while embodying the
official, the grandiose language

04:15:59.720 --> 04:16:04.230
and larger than life behaviors
as well as idealistic love

04:16:04.230 --> 04:16:07.930
to sacrifice for the Motherland.

04:16:07.930 --> 04:16:11.940
Concurrently, the first Pahlavi's
Women Emancipation Program

04:16:11.940 --> 04:16:16.640
in 1936 facilitated the
men's presence on stage.

04:16:16.640 --> 04:16:20.230
However, public performance
and especially dancing

04:16:20.230 --> 04:16:24.510
for Muslim women continued
to have its predicaments.

04:16:24.510 --> 04:16:29.510
As I argue in my book, these early
combinations of music, dance,

04:16:29.510 --> 04:16:31.970
and acting with Iranian literature

04:16:31.970 --> 04:16:36.240
and nationalist themes
gave legitimacy to dance

04:16:36.240 --> 04:16:41.010
and revered asexual female
performers appeared on stage

04:16:41.010 --> 04:16:44.710
as angels and Persian princesses.

04:16:44.710 --> 04:16:50.980
Such depiction of women as angel
and Persian princesses combined

04:16:50.980 --> 04:16:53.400
with nationalist and
revivalist attitude

04:16:53.400 --> 04:16:58.090
for ancient Iranian tradition
